<DOCNO> XIE20000501.0004 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Nigerians Satisfied With Obasanjo's Governance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Most of Nigerians are satisfied
with the performance of President Olusegun Obasanjo's government,
the News Agency of Nigeria reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The survey, named as "Attitudes Toward Democracy and Markets in
Nigeria", was conducted in Nigeria between January and February by
the U.S.-based International Foundation for Election Systems and
Management Systems International.
</P>
<P>
It showed that nearly 87 percent of Nigerians had high
expectations that their standard of living would improve in a
year, while 71 percent expected the government to fulfill its
promises within four years.
</P>
<P>
The survey also indicated that a very high percentage of
Nigerians rejected non-democratic alternatives and a proposition
that "the army should come in to govern the country", noting that
Nigerians' quest for democracy was unmatched in comparison to
survey results in other countries of the African continent.
</P>
<P>
"An overwhelming 80.9 percent think democracy is preferable to
any other form of government", it stated, adding "75.3 percent
believe in freedom of expression, while 79.2 percent reject the
use of violence for political ends".
</P>
<P>
More than 80 percent of Nigerians expressed satisfaction with
the government's workings of democracy, it added.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo's civil government came into power last May after the
long-term military rule of the west African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
