<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Jewish Suspect Confesses to Spying for Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Hamid Tefilin, one of the 13 Iranian
Jews arrested on espionage charges, confessed on Monday night to
having spied for Israel, state television reported.
</P>
<P>
"I am guilty. I accept the charges against me. I spied for
Israel," Tefilin said in an interview with the television after the
second session of the closed-door trial on the Iranian accused of
spying for Iran's arch foes, the United States and Israel.
</P>
<P>
The report said that four of the 13 Jews appeared at the court
hearing held Monday in Shiraz, the southern Fars province, where
they were arrested along with eight Iranian Muslims in March and
April last year.
</P>
<P>
Tefilin is the main suspect of the group of Jews. Earlier
reports said that four of the suspects had already confessed to
their crimes at the first court hearing.
</P>
<P>
Head of the provincial justice department Ali Amiri assured the
families of the Jewish defendants that they would face a fair and
just trial.
</P>
<P>
He said the trial would be held once a week in Shiraz, the
center of Iran's 35,000-strong Jewish community.
</P>
<P>
The first session of the closed-door trial was held on April 13
and was adjourned upon the request of a defense lawyer. The second
hearing was put off until after the Jewish holiday of Passover.
</P>
<P>
The Western countries expressed grave concern over the trial and
demanded release of the Iranian Jews after the U.S. and Israel
denied any links between their intelligence services and the
accused.
</P>
<P>
Tehran, however, rejected any "foreign interference" in the
trial. 
</P>
</TEXT>
