<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Calls for Compensation for U.S.-Led Military Strikes in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Iraq Monday urged the 2000
Review Conference of the Parties to the Treaty on the Non-
Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons (NPT) to condemn the acts of
aggression by the United States and Britain in December 1998 and
compensate it for the damage it suffered.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the general debate of the Review Conference, which
is held here from April 24 to May 19, Iraq's Ambassador to the
United Nations Saeed Hasan said, "In addition to being an
illegitimate use of force against an independent state without the
authorization of the Security Council, the aggression gave a fatal
blow to the IAEA's (International Atomic Energy Agency) monitoring
regime in Iraq."
</P>
<P>
Hasan charged that monitoring instruments as well as the sites
themselves had been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq is in full compliance with all its obligations under the
Non-Proliferation Treaty and IAEA's safeguards regime," the
ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
Hasan strongly condemned Israel for being the only Middle East
nation not a party to the NPT.
</P>
<P>
"The international community and its organizations have the
legal responsibility to force Israel to join the NPT and place its
nuclear facilities under the IAEA's safeguard regime," Hasan said.
</P>
<P>
He called on the Review Conference to adopt recommendations to
implement fully a Middle East resolution by the 1995 conference so
as to send a clear message to Israel to accede to the treaty
without further delay.
</P>
<P>
The United Sates and Britain launched four-day military
strikes against Iraq in December 1998 under the pretext that Iraq
had not cooperated fully with the U.N. arms inspectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
