<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four U.N. Envoys Initiate GA Special Session on AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Four U.N. Envoys Monday
called on the United Nations General Assembly (GA) to convene a
special session next year to address the issue of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The initiative was made by Bernd Niehaus of Costa Rica,
Vladimir Galuska of the Czech Republic, Volodymyr Yel'schenko of
Ukraine and Tichaona Joseph Jokonya of Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the U.N. secretary-general, the envoys
recommended the AIDS issue be added to the agenda of the current
General Assembly to enable it to adopt a resolution calling for a
special session some time in May 2001.
</P>
<P>
In a memorandum, they said HIV had infected 50 million people
since the start of he epidemic, 33.6 million of whom were still
alive.
</P>
<P>
The four envoys said that the situation of HIV-AIDS had over
the past few years been worsening.
</P>
<P>
"Because the epidemic strikes people in their most productive
years, those aged between 15 and 49, HIV/AIDS will have greater
social and economic impact than other diseases in the most
affected areas," they noted.
</P>
<P>
It was high time for the United Nations to elaborate a
comprehensive agenda for action against the epidemic and to
convene a special session of the General Assembly to review the
problem of HIV/AIDS in all its aspects, and to propose new
strategies to strengthen international cooperation, they added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
