<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Solana Says EU Unwilling to Back U.S. Missile Defense System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Solana indicated that the best way for the United States to go
ahead was to seek Russia's approval for a new missile defense.
</P>
<P>
"We would like to see it done in such a manner that the
relationship is not disturbed in such a way that we have a major
crisis with Europe," he added.
</P>
<P>
Noting that existing arms control measures have worked well,
Solana said that "it is very difficult to explain to Europeans
there is a risk," but adding "potentially there may be a threat."
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration is to decide whether the United
States should deploy a national missile defense (NMD) system
against missile threat from "rogue" states. The project was
opposed by Russia and even U.S. allies in Europe like France.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration is currently trying to persuade
Russia to agree to amend the Anti-ballistic Missile (ABM) Treaty
signed by Moscow and Washington in 1972, which bans the deployment
of the NMD system.
</P>
<P>
Solana told reporters the Europeans would like to see an
agreement with Moscow as well as a debate on the merits of the
missile defense program before President Clinton goes ahead.
</P>
<P>
Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov reiterated during his
visit to Washington last week that his country continues
opposition to NMD and changes to the ABM treaty.
</P>
<P>
Solana said Russian President Vladimir Putin told him in Moscow
on April 9 that he had not agreed to negotiate changes in the
treaty and did not intend to "in the near future." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
