<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.African President Pledges Commitment to DRC Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 1 (Xinhua) -- South Africa would keep its
commitment to a resolution of the Democratic Republic of the
Congo (DRC) conflict, President Thabo Mbeki said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
South Africa should keep being involved with the DRC problem,
Mbeki said at a meeting with business people in Mabopane, north of
Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
A unit of the South African National Defence Force was on
stand-by to join other United Nations troops as part of the
implementation of the peace agreement signed by the parties
concerned, Mbeki said.
</P>
<P>
If the problem in the DRC was not addressed, it would not go
away, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki returned from Algiers on Monday morning following a
meeting with African leaders on the war in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
From the meeting it was clear that part of the reason why the
situation in that country remained, was because certain decisions
had not been carried out, Mbeki said, adding that "all these
things agreed to had not been done."
</P>
<P>
All had agreed that the war in the DRC must end, that the
Congolese people should have their own leaders and that they
should agree about a constitutional government, democratic
constitution and an election date, he said.
</P>
<P>
The decisions taken by the African leaders on Sunday would
result in something being done to end the war, the withdrawal of
all foreign troops from the DRC and the Congolese people deciding
what to do about their country, Mbeki said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
