<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Medical Group Calls for Flu Vaccination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The low rate of vaccine uptake by South Africans was attributed
to the fact that cold weather had not yet struck and that the
influenza season had not properly started, Medinfo spokesman
Stephen Toovey said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
It was also untrue that the vaccine would prove ineffective if
not taken by the end of April, he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is never too late to vaccinate. While it is imperative that
high risk individuals such as diabetics, asthmatics, heart
sufferers, the elderly and the immuno-compromised be immunized,
the vaccine makes good sense for all," he said.
</P>
<P>
Research showed that exposure to inactivated influenza viruses
could slow the rate at which the human immunodeficiency virus
replicated in AIDS patients, Toovey said.
</P>
<P>
"Although further research work is awaited on this topic, we do
know that people living with HIV should definitely be protected
against influenza by vaccination," he said.
</P>
<P>
Two types of influenza virus A have been detected in South
Africa while another strain, influenza B, is expected to arrive
later in the season.
</P>
<P>
Strains of influenza circulating in the southern hemisphere
this year include Sydney and New Caledonia (both are influenza A
strains), and Yamanashi (an influenza B strain). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000501.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Trade Unions Call for General Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 1 (Xinhua) -- About 1.8 million South African
workers are expected to go on strike on May 10 to protest job
losses.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the Congress of South African Trade Unions told
a May Day rally here on Monday that the union, which claims a
membership of 1.8 million people, intended to go ahead with its
general strike on May 10 after the government and business failed
to respond to its three-month campaign against job losses.
</P>
<P>
In a show of solidarity, the ruling African National Congress
Secretary- General Kgalema Motlanthe told the crowd his party
supported the call for the general strike.
</P>
<P>
"Only through action and mass mobilization will we be able to
achieve our goals," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party Secretary-General Blade Nzimande said his
party would also throw its weight behind the call for the May 10
strike. 
</P>
</TEXT>
