<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Condemns Israel's Settlement Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat on
Monday condemned Israeli government's approval of publishing new
settlement expansion tender in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint conference with visiting Australian Prime
Minister John Howard in the Palestinian self-rule city of Gaza,
Arafat said the tender for settlements expansion was negative and
destructive to the Israeli-Palestinian peace track.
</P>
<P>
It was the first public reaction from Arafat to last Thursday's
decision of Israel's Construction and Housing Ministry to issue a
tender for building 174 new housing units in Ma'aleh Adumim, a
mammoth Jewish settlement near Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The news, which emerged only on Sunday's Hebrew newspapers,
angered the Palestinian negotiators in Israel's Red Sea resort of
Eilat, where they were beginning to hold a further round of talks
with their Israeli counterparts to reach a framework agreement on
final-status issues by May.
</P>
<P>
The final-status issues include the return of Palestinian
refugees, the status of Jerusalem, Jewish settlements, borders,
security and water.
</P>
<P>
The settlement expansion crisis reportedly postponed the
beginning of the Eilat talks for more than five hours and
undermined the confidence of the Palestinians in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
According to Arafat, the Palestinian delegation had submitted a
protest letter on the subject, which Israeli negotiators agreed to
review after their return to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Arafat reiterated the Palestinians' rights to declare
an independent state on the West Bank and Gaza Strip this
September. "It needs to be made clear that a Palestinian state is a
natural right of the Palestinian people," he said at the news
conference with Howard.
</P>
<P>
Arafat was in response to remarks by chief Israeli negotiator
Oded Eran earlier in the day that a Palestinian state will be the
outcome of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Before the news conference, Arafat briefed Howard, who arrived
in the region last Saturday on a four-day visit, about progress in
the Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
Howard said that he saw a "very strong personal commitment" by
Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak, whom Howard met in
Jerusalem on Sunday, to seize the peace opportunities.
</P>
<P>
He also promised on Sunday to encourage and support the peace
initiatives of "the principal players" at a diplomatic level.
</P>
<P>
The Australian leader is scheduled to meet with Israeli
President Ezer Weizman and attend Israel's Holocaust Memorial Day
ceremonies at the Yad Vashem Holocaust Memorial as honored guest
later on Monday.
</P>
<P>
He will also meet Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy before
leaving Israel on Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
