<DOCNO> XIE20000501.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs from
the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- A study conducted by the World Tourism and Travel
Council (WTTC) said that revenues from the tourism sector in Turkey
will reach 73.4 billion U.S. dollars in 2010, reported Turkish
Daily News on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Tourism revenues in 2000 are expected to account for 13.2
percent of the Turkish gross national product (GNP).
</P>
<P>
The study predicted that the tourism sector will provide jobs
for 1.5 million people in Turkey in a decade. It said the share of
personal income spent on tourism will rise to 10.1 percent and
private investment in tourism will reach 13.2 billion dollars by
2010.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Travel Agencies' Association Chairman Basaran Ulusoy
said that while in 1980 the number of tourists visiting Turkey was
1.2 million and revenue from tourism totaled 326 million dollars,
these figures had increased to 9.7 million and 7.1 billion dollars
by 1998.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The Istanbul Stock Exchange (IMKB) was listed as the
fourth heaviest trading among emerging markets in the first two
months of 2000, reported Turkish Daily News on monday.
</P>
<P>
The Federation Internationale des Bourses de Valeurs (FIBV)
announced that Chinese Taipei Exchange topped the FIBV list with a
trade volume of 250.6 billion dollars in January and February this
year. South Korea followed with 127 billion dollars and Hong Kong
with 99 billion.
</P>
<P>
Two-month trading in the IMKB amounted to 43 billion dollars,
followed by the Athens Exchange with 28.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- The National Iranian Oil Company (NIOC) and nine
international oil companies have reached an agreement on a 25-year
project to study Iranian gas reserves, Director of the British oil
company Lasmo on business for Iran Keyhan Karbasi said here on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the Islamic Republic News Agency, Karbasi said that
identifying gas reserves, estimating the volume of the reserves,
amount of domestic consumption and feasibility of gas exports
constitute the major dimensions of the study.
</P>
<P>
The companies participating in the project include Lasmo,
British Petroleum, Shell, Gaz de France, British Gas, BHP
Australia, Petronas of Malaysia, Agip of Italy and Elf of France,
he said.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iranian Commerce Minister Mohammad Shariatmadari said
on Sunday that his country expects to earn 4.4 billion dollars from
non-oil exports in the current Iranian calendar year, which started
on March 20.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in Orumieh, the capital of West Azarbaijan province,
Shariatmadari said his ministry has eased the regulations
concerning the export of goods, the Islamic Republic News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
He put the figure last Iranian year at 3.22 billion dollars with
a 10.3 percent increase from the previous year. But he added that
the figure only included the exports which were conducted through
deposit of drafts for repatriation of hard currency earned from
exports.
</P>
<P>
Governor of the Central Bank of Iran Mohsen Nourbakhsh said
earlier this month that the country earned 3.5 billion dollars from
non-oil exports during the past Iranian year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
