<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Candidate Passes Second Round Voting for Turkish Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 1 (Xinhua) -- None of the presidential candidates
won 367 votes, or a two-third majority in the 550-seat parliament,
to be elected the next Turkish president in the second round of
ballot in the parliament on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Ahmet Necdet Sezer, the presiding judge of the Constitutional
Court who is the single candidate of the five parties represented
in the legislature, scored the highest number of votes with 314, up
from 281 in the first round last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Before the ballot that started at 15:05 local time (1205 GMT),
three candidates, Oguz Aygun from Democratic Left Party (DSP), Agah
Guner from the Motherland Party (ANAP) and Ahmet Iyimaya from the
True Path Party (DYP), withdrew from the race.
</P>
<P>
The other seven contenders, therefore, were competing in this
round of ballot during which a total of 532 deputies cast their
votes with five invalid.
</P>
<P>
The parliament Speaker Yildirim Akbulut was seen rising in this
election, ranking second with 88 votes. Considered the strongest
challenger for Sezer, Akbulut ranked only fourth with 56 votes in
the first round.
</P>
<P>
The other five candidates won votes ranging from 2 to 66, far
behind the two leading contenders.
</P>
<P>
According to the election procedures, if no candidate wins two-
thirds of the votes in the first two rounds, the parliament will
hold the third round of voting on May 5.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that Sezer and Akbulut will be the two strongest
contenders in this key round during which 276 votes will be
sufficient. The advantage of Sezer increased progressively with the
election going ahead, they noted.
</P>
<P>
Akbulut said on Monday that he will persist in the race till the
final moment, adding that neither positioning a consensus candidate
nor imposing pressure on deputies is "democratic," obviously
referring to the unanimous backing Sezer received from leaders of
the legislative parties.
</P>
<P>
Sezer is the joint candidate of the three ruling parties and the
two main oppositions. The five parties' leaders expect to have
Sezer elected by the end of the first three rounds without having
to stage a fourth and final round.
</P>
<P>
In case of failure, two candidates who win the highest votes in
the third round attend the last round. If agreement can not be
reached, the parliament will be dissolved immediatly for new
general elections in accordance with the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
The Grand National Assembly (parliament) chooses the president
over a maximum of four rounds of voting that must end before
incumbent President Suleyman Demirel's tenure expires on May 16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
