<HEADLINE> 6 Injured in Mortar Explosions in Tehran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 1 (Xinhua) -- At least six people were wounded in a
mortar attack Monday evening near an Iranian military headquarters
in northern Tehran, the state television reported.
</P>
<P>
The television said that a number of mortars hit at least five
spots in a sports complex in the Ararat Street around 20:15 hours
local times (1545 GMT) and one of the injured is in critical
conditions.
</P>
<P>
The security forces rushed to the explosion spots, about 500
meters south of the headquarters of the Islamic Revolutionary
Guards Corps (IRGC) and the security forces.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Iran's main military opposition Mujaheddin
Khalq Organization (MKO) has claimed responsibility for the attack.
</P>
<P>
Monday's attack came several weeks after four people were
wounded on March 13 in mortar attacks launched by the MKO at IRGC
headquarters in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
On February 5, the MKO fired seven mortar shells to an area
close to Iranian government buildings including the presidential
office, killing one person and injuring four others.
</P>
<P>
The Iraq-based MKO has become more active in stage infiltration
and sabotage operations inside Iran, making use of the rift and
intensified power struggle between conservatives loyal to the
Islamic Revolution and reformist allied with President Mohammad
Khatami.
</P>
<P>
Iran said it smashed a three-member MKO group on Saturday in the
border province of Ilam. Two MKO members and a police officer were
killed after the MKO members exploded their hideout.
</P>
<P>
A famous political-military group which fought against the late
shah's regime in the 1970s, the MKO was outlawed in 1981 and forced
to flee to Iraq after splitting with the ruling clergy, brought to
power by the 1979 Islamic Revolution. 
</P>
<P>
Accused as a terrorist group by Tehran, the MKO carried out a
series of cross-border attacks and assassinations of senior Iranian
officials in recent years. In retaliation, Iran air-raided MKO
bases inside Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
