<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Leader Urges Removal of Investment Blocks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni on
Monday called for removal of obstacles to investment to create
more jobs.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the nation on the International Labor Day, Museveni
said that 81,000 jobs have been created by new enterprises since
1991, but "these changes have not been fast enough to keep pace
with the increasing demands for employment".
</P>
<P>
Museveni said "the obstacles to investments in the country
include bureaucratic delays, high bank interest rates, unfair or
delayed court decisions on disputes and a strong imports lobby in
government departments."
</P>
<P>
He said the government and the whole system in the country are
not investor-friendly, but either hostile, indifferent or
inconsiderate to investors.
</P>
<P>
The president called on all Ugandans to understand and
appreciate the connection between investment, economic growth and
employment creation.
</P>
<P>
Museveni also stressed the importance of regional integration
to create a large market, saying, "the integration will make the
region a more attractive investment destination." 
</P>
</TEXT>
