<HEADLINE> Japan Donates Food Aid to Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Japan will extend emergency food
aid worth 4.8 million U.S. dollars through the United Nations
World Food Program (WFP) to assist drought-hit people in Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
The government of Japan decided to make the donation in
recognition that without prompt international assistance, a large
scale famine may follow, the Japanese Embassy in Ethiopia said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Due to the shortage of rainfall in the past three years, the
impact of drought has been spreading in the Horn of Africa with
over 8 million people affected in Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Prior to Japan's donation, the United States, France, Britain,
Spain, Israel and China, among others, have either donated relief
food or money to Ethiopia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
