<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Key Events Leading to Lockerbie Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAMP ZEIST, the Netherlands, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Following are
the key events that have preceded the long-awaited trial of the
two Libyans suspected of bombing Pan Am flight 103 on December 21,
1988:
</P>
<P>
1988:
</P>
<P>
December 21 -- Pan Am flight 103 was blown over the Scottish
village of Lockerbie, killing 259 people on board and 11 others on
the ground;
</P>
<P>
1989:
</P>
<P>
October 30 -- German investigators said that a suitcase coming
to Frankfurt aboard an Air Malta flight believed to contain the
Lockerbie bomb;
</P>
<P>
1991:
</P>
<P>
November 14 -- United States and Scottish authorities indicted
two Libyans allegedly linked to the Lockerbie bombing;
</P>
<P>
1992:
</P>
<P>
January 21 -- United Nations Security Council Resolution 731
demanded handover of the alleged suspects;
</P>
<P>
April 15 -- United Nations Security Council Resolution 748
imposed sanctions upon Libya;
</P>
<P>
1993:
</P>
<P>
March 18 -- Libya offered to hand over suspects to neutral
country for trial; United States and Britain rejected the offer;
</P>
<P>
November 11 -- United Nations Security Council Resolution 883
strengthened sanctions imposed on Libya;
</P>
<P>
1994:
</P>
<P>
March 22 -- Libya offered to put suspects on trial before
Scottish judges at the International Court of Justice;
</P>
<P>
April 15 -- United States rejected the offer;
</P>
<P>
1998:
</P>
<P>
April 15 -- Families of the Lockerbie bombing victims urged the
United States and Britain to accept the Libyan offer of a trial in
a neutral country;
</P>
<P>
June 10 -- The Organization of African Unity announced that it
would no longer abide by the U.N. air embargo sanction;
</P>
<P>
August 24 -- The United States and Britain accepted the Libyan
offer of a trial in the Netherlands under Scottish laws, with
Britain insisting that if convicted, the two Libyans would serve
their sentences in Scotland;
</P>
<P>
August 27 -- United Nations Security Council Resolution 1192
endorsed British and American offer to hold a trial under Scots
Law before a Scottish court sitting in the Netherlands;
</P>
<P>
September 18 -- Camp Zeist near the Dutch city of Utrecht was
chosen as the trial site;
</P>
<P>
1999:
</P>
<P>
March 19 -- Colonel Quadhafi announced that the two suspects
would be handed over;
</P>
<P>
April 5 -- Libya extradited Abdel Basset Ali al-Megrahi and
Lamen Khalifa Fhimah to the Netherlands; United Nations suspended
sanctions;
</P>
<P>
November 18 -- Judges were appointed;
</P>
<P>
December 8 -- Defendants made first public appearance at a Camp
Zeist pre-trial hearing;
</P>
<P>
December 9 -- Judge rejected defense motion to throw murder
conspiracy charge;
</P>
<P>
2000:
</P>
<P>
February 2 -- Defense lawyers entered innocent pleas;
</P>
<P>
April 27 -- Judge rejected a prosecution bid to delay the start
of the trial after the defense delayed the start of the trial
twice (on June 7, 1999 and on December 7, 1999);
</P>
<P>
May 1 -- Media center at Camp Zeist opened to the press with
accreditation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000501.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Key Figures in Lockerbie Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAMP ZEIST, the Netherlands, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Following are
the key figures involved in the coming trial of the two Libyans
accused of bombing Pan Am flight 103 on December 21, 1988:
</P>
<P>
Defendants:
</P>
<P>
Abdel Basset Ali al-Megrahi -- Security chief for the Libyan
Arab Airlines and formerly director of the center for strategic
studies in Libya; allegedly bought clothes contained in a suitcase
holding the Lockerbie bomb;
</P>
<P>
Lamen Khalifa Fhimah -- Manager of the Libyan Arab Airlines
station in Malta; allegedly had access to Air Malta luggage tags
that facilitated the suitcase containing the bomb to get on board
the New York-bound flight;
</P>
<P>
Defense lawyers:
</P>
<P>
William Taylor -- Representing al-Magrahi;
</P>
<P>
Richard Keen -- Representing Fhimah;
</P>
<P>
Court Officers:
</P>
<P>
Lord Sutherland Ranald Lain Sutherland -- Presiding judge;
</P>
<P>
Lord Coulsfield John Taylor Cameron -- Judge;
</P>
<P>
Lord Maclean Ranald Norman Munro Maclean -- Judge;
</P>
<P>
Lord Abernethy John Alastair Cameron -- Additional judge;
</P>
<P>
Prosecution:
</P>
<P>
Lord Advocate Colin Boyd QC -- Chief prosecutor;
</P>
</TEXT>
