<HEADLINE> Chinese Ambassador Becomes Security Council President for May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Wang Yingfan, Chinese
permanent representative to the United Nations, succeeded Robert
Fowler, Canadian ambassador to the United Nations, as the
president of the U.N. Security Council as of May 1.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time for Ambassador Wang to take over as the
president of the 15-member Security Council since he became the
Chinese permanent representative to the United Nations in February.
</P>
<P>
The Council presidency changes monthly according to the
principle of alphabetical rotation among the 15 members, including
the five permanent members.
</P>
<P>
Under the U.N. Charter, the Security council has the primary
responsibility for the maintenance of peace and security in the
world at large. 
</P>
</TEXT>
