<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000501.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council to Meet on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Monday began a meeting behind closed doors to hear the briefing by
the head of a U.N. delegation which just returned from a visit to
Kosovo, a Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
The 15-member Council will be briefed by Anwarul Chowdhury,
head of the U.N. delegation, at the closed-door meeting on the
first day of the month.
</P>
<P>
Chowdhury, Bangladesh's permanent representative to the United
Nations, said on April 29 in Pristina, capital of Kosovo Province
in Yugoslavia, that the U.N. delegation had ended a three-day tour
and was convinced there was no need to alter or replace Security
Council Resolution 1244, which created a U.N. mission in Kosovo,
but implementation must be improved.
</P>
<P>
He said that the U.N. Interim Administration Mission in Kosovo
(UNMIK) was seriously short of administrators -- less than half
the full level by some estimates -- and police and that much more
effort was needed to free prisoners and account for missing people.
</P>
<P>
"We found a serious constraint with regard to staffing, both
civilian police and administration. I believe we have to address
this point when we are back in New York," he said.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh was elected by the General Assembly last year to
join the Security Council this year as one of 10 non-permanent
members for the two-year terms.
</P>
<P>
He said that refugee returns had to be another priority,
together with the missing and detainees, if ethnic reconciliation
was to be achieved and democracy established in the Serbian
province.
</P>
<P>
"While we encourage returns, we have to be able to receive
them properly," he said. "The question of security, accommodation
and livelihood are issues that must be addressed at the same time.
"  
</P>
</TEXT>
