<DOCNO> XIE20000501.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Construction Spending Rises in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Spending by the U.S. government
and the private sector on construction projects rose by 1.4
percent in March, the third straight monthly increase this year,
the Commerce Department reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The construction spending, which was driven by a burst of
activity in big government projects, increased to a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of 765.2 billion U.S. dollars last month.
</P>
<P>
In January, construction spending rose nearly 2 percent and in
February it went up by 1.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve has boosted interest rates five times since
June to slow the speeding economy and keep inflation under control.
Given the outlook for strong continuing growth, many economists
believe the Fed will raise interest rates on May 16 and again in
June.
</P>
<P>
Even with an upswing in interest rates, robust construction and
housing activity helped fuel the economy's strong growth last year.
Monday's report suggested that higher interest rates still haven't
significantly dampened activity in this sector.
</P>
<P>
Spending on big government projects posted the biggest gain in
March, rising 2.8 percent to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of
178.4 billion dollars. Increased spending on highways and streets,
schools and housing more than offset decreased spending on
hospitals, industrial buildings and military facilities.
</P>
<P>
The construction report showed that spending on all
nonresidential, or commercial building, grew 1.4 percent to a rate
of 201.2 billion dollars. Spending on industrial buildings,
offices and hotels and motels all rose.
</P>
<P>
Spending on all residential projects also went up 1.4 percent
to a rate of 344.1 billion dollars as spending on single-family
homes declined, while spending on apartment buildings and condos
rose.
</P>
<P>
All private construction projects, which includes residential
and commercial activity, saw spending grow by 0.9 percent in March
to a rate of 568.8 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
