<HEADLINE> International Labor Day Celebrated in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Chinese across the country crowded
into scenic spots, recreation centers, shopping malls and
bookstores today, getting a busy start on their first-ever week-
long spring holiday marking International Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 of the nation's model workers, who were honored
by the central government here on Sunday, were invited to the
traditional flag-raising ceremony at Tiananmen Square early this
morning, and to sightsee throughout the capital city.
</P>
<P>
Parks, recreational centers and shopping malls in the city were
filled with vacationers out to enjoy the warmest day so far this
year.
</P>
<P>
A long-distance run activity in Shanghai attracted lots of
local people. The event organized by the Shanghai Municipal
Federation of Trade Unions has been held for 14 years, with more
than 300,000 people participating.
</P>
<P>
Book fairs are a new twist in the holiday activities in many
Chinese cities such as Beijing, Tianjin and Changchun, capital of
northeast China's Jilin Province.
</P>
<P>
At the Changchun Union Book City, more than 400 domestic
publishing houses displayed some 80,000 titles.
</P>
<P>
"This is indeed a festival for us book lovers, and I'll enjoy
all these books during the holiday," said Fu Guojia, a high school
student at the Changchun No. 104 Middle School.
</P>
<P>
More than one million residents in Guangzhou chose to celebrate
Labor Day today by leaving town for scenic locales. All tickets
for flights to popular domestic destinations were sold out several
days ago.
</P>
<P>
Concerts and choral performances by groups of workers are the
customary Labor Day events in the cities of Tianjin, Shanghai and
Yinchuan,capital of Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region in northwest
China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
