<DOCNO> XIE20000501.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Vows to Effect Democratic Transition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Myanmar military
government said it is firmly resolved to effect a democratic
transition, but it pointed out, however, that undue foreign
interference will only stifle both political and socioeconomic
development of the country, thus unnecessarily delaying further
political change.
</P>
<P>
An official Information Sheet Monday quoted a recent news
release of the Myanmar Embassy in London as saying the democratic
transition can only be effected by a government capable of not
only achieving peace with all its nationalities but also defending
the sovereignty and integrity of the country.
</P>
<P>
"Times have changed drastically since 1947 and a repeat of that
history of significant foreign interference is simply no longer
possible," it stated.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the Kayin National Union (KNU), the largest anti-
government ethnic armed group that is still operating on the
Myanmar-Thai border and has not made peace yet with the government,
the Information Sheet said the government has continuously offered
the group terms of peace similar to those already achieved with 17
other decades-old armed groups in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The Information Sheet accused the KNU of having chosen to fight
the first constitutionally elected government half a century ago,
saying the group's military campaign has been on a downhill course
over the years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000501.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Djibouti Conference on Somalia Overshadowed by Fighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Over 100 Somali representatives
from various clans and political groups Monday left for Djibouti
to attend a peace conference to be opened on Tuesday despite that
the fighting in North Mogadishu could worsen to a larger scale.
</P>
<P>
While many Somalis are excited about the opening of the
conference in Djibouti, many others have been fleeing their houses
in fear of the fighting between rival sides within the Eli-Omar
and Rer-Matan subclans of the Abgal community in Karan district of
North Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The fighting, which changed from its random retaliatory attacks
against each other to a real and serious armed confrontation on
Sunday, has already caused havoc in the business and ordinary life
in Karan and Yaqshid districts.
</P>
<P>
As the fighting intensified in the early hours of Monday, the
rival militiamen of Eli-Omar and Rer-Matan clans started using
mortar shells and the anti-tank guns of B-10 against each other's
positions in order to dislodge the rival side.
</P>
<P>
There are no exact casualty figures available at this stage;
however, stray rounds of B-10 guns have claimed the lives of more
than five people including a woman and a four-year old girl.
</P>
<P>
According to Abdullahi Yussuf Elvis, Deputy Director of the
International Committee of the Red Cross - run Kaysaney Hospital,
22 victims of the war have reached their hospital for treatment.
</P>
<P>
Eight people were hit by bullets while the rest suffered
shrapnel wounds from B-10 and rocket-propelled grenades, Elvis
said, adding that none of the war patients has so far died of
their wounds although the wounded are still flowing into the
hospital wards.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, the Al-Hayat private hospital in South Mogadishu
has registered the death of one young lady while treating several
others, but only one man now remains in the hospital for further
treatment.
</P>
<P>
According to local FM radio station of Mogadishu, Horn-Afrique
has also reported the death of eight people in Sunday's fighting.
</P>
<P>
As the damage of fighting increased dramatically on Monday,
well-known traditional leaders such as Sheikh Ali Dhereh and Haji
Ali Daud tried to make a cease-fire by organizing a demonstration
attended by hundreds of children and women.
</P>
<P>
The children and women took to the streets where the rival
militiamen had been in defensive positions, forcing them to stop
the shooting. "No more civil war, no more bloodshed" were among
the words used to ease the tension of the combat militiamen.
</P>
<P>
This is not the first time that a cease-fire is brokered between
the two sides. But a lasting solution seems to be beyond the reach
of the elders in Mogadishu since the conflict roots back to
problems in the countryside where the two sides quarrel over the
ownership of lands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000501.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qatar to Host Asian Table Tennis Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Doha, May 1 (Xinhua) -- A successful of the Asian table tennis
championships will be a booster on Qatar's quest to hosting the
2006 Asian Games, the nation's sports official believes.
</P>
<P>
"I am confident that this championships will be a great success
and will provide good indication on Qatar's capability of hosting
such a prestigious event as the Asian Games," Abdullah Al-Mullah,
Tournament Director of the championships was quoted as saying by
Qatar's English language daily the Peninsula on Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said that the hosting of the Qatar Open Tournaments last
year had helped the Gulf emirate earn the respect of both the
International Table Tennis Federation (ITTF) and the Asian Table
Tennis Union (ATTU).
</P>
<P>
Al-Mullah appealed both Qataris and the sizeable expatriate
community here to visit the games and cheer their favorite players.
</P>
<P>
The 15th Asian Table Tennis Championships will run from May 3
to 8 in the Qatari capital of Doha.
</P>
<P>
Players from around 30 Asian countries and regions will compete
for the seven events -- team, singles and doubles both for men and
women, and the mixed doubles.
</P>
<P>
Up till Monday, some of the national teams, including the
competitive Japanese and South Korean squads, have already arrived
here for preparations.
</P>
<P>
Powerhouse China will only send its women players here for the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
The 14th Asian Table Tennis Championships was held in the
Japanese city of Osaka in September 1998, with the participation
of 401 players from across the Asian continent.
</P>
<P>
China won six out the seven champions as the South Korean pair
overcame their Chinese counterparts in the women's doubles' final.
</P>
</TEXT>
