<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unemployed Workers in Bangladesh to Get Jobs After Training </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina Monday said workers of state-run factories who went on
voluntary retirement or lost jobs in the privatization process
would be re-employed after being trained under a government scheme.
</P>
<P>
"We have undertaken initiatives for the re-employment of these
workers in new units after imparting training," the prime minister
told an International Labor Day discussion attended by government
officials and workers' representatives.
</P>
<P>
The government also decided to set up new units in the premises
of the privatized factories, to ensure maximum utilization of
industrial plots and reduce pressure on agricultural lands,she
added.
</P>
<P>
Hasina further said the government has set up 29 workers'
welfare centers including seven new ones for tea garden workers
and four industrial institutions across the country to oversee the
workers' welfare and increase their efficiency.
</P>
<P>
So far 1,200 government officials, owners and workers have
undergone training in these institutions and 1,800 workers have
been provided with skill development training at the welfare
centers, she said.
</P>
<P>
Turning to the private sector units, Hasina said that in many
cases, the workers have been subjected to exploitation and at
times the private owners even misappropriate the provident fund of
the employees, causing labor unrest and other problems.
</P>
<P>
She said the government is planning to enact a new law to
prevent misappropriation of provident fund money of the factory
workers.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said her government has already approved the
National Wage Commission recommendations for increased wages,
adding that she has asked the concerned authorities to implement
the new wage structure as soon as possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
