<DOCNO> XIE20000501.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Government Calls Banking System Solid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government assured the
public Monday that the country's banking system remains one of the
most solid in Asia, with the closure of Urban Bank strictly being
an isolated case.
</P>
<P>
This assurance was made by Director General Felipe Medalla of
the National Economic and Development Authority, Secretary Jose
Pardo of the Department of Finance and Governor Rafael
Buenaventura of the Central Bank of the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The three officials told reporters in the Presidential Palace
that the central bank and the Bankers Association of the
Philippines (BAP) are ready to address all cash requirements of
private banks through the establishment of a "liquidity pool."
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Joseph Estrada ordered the managers last
Friday to ensure the stability of the banking system following
Urban Bank's closure and the subsequent heavy withdrawals
experienced by two other commercial banks, the International
Exchange Bank (I-Bank) and the Philippine Bank of Communications (
PBCom).
</P>
<P>
The capability of the central bank and the BAP to set up a
liquidity pool to meet all cash requirements, Buenaventura said,
attests to the stability and solidity of the country's banking
system.
</P>
<P>
Under this setup, banks line up their securities and other
assets so that they can readily be converted into cash through the
liquidity pool when the need arises.
</P>
<P>
Buenaventura also pointed out that the cases of I-Bank and
PBCom,which remain solvent, are entirely different from Urban Bank,
which declared a bank holiday last Thursday since it could not
immediately meet its heavy withdrawal demands.
</P>
<P>
I-Bank and PBCom, according to Buenaventura, were victims of
false rumors concerning their financial conditions.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Medalla stressed that the country's banking system
"is solid and their assets are more than enough to pay for all the
liabilities."
</P>
<P>
Finance Secretary Pardo assured I-Bank and PBCom clients that
checks issued by these banks are being honored.
</P>
<P>
"If you should run into problems like this, please refer it to
the BAP, the central bank or even the finance department and we'll
be pleased to help you," Pardo said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
