<DOCNO> XIE20000501.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Makes Efforts to Transform Workforce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Singapore has been making efforts
to transform its workforce so as to prepare for new competition
and tap new opportunities in the New Economy.
</P>
<P>
"The School of Lifelong Learning is our strategy to help
workers achieve higher skills and lifelong employability,"
Singapore Minister for Manpower Lee Boon Yang said on the
transformation of his country's 1.9 million-strong workforce while
delivering a speech at the May Day rally held Monday by the
National Trades Union of Singapore.
</P>
<P>
The School of Lifelong Learning is Singapore's key national
initiative and system aimed at enabling individuals to access
quality education and training on an ongoing basis and at
encouraging enterprises to invest in human capital development.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Manpower and its partners from the public,
private and people sectors recently launched the Singapore
Learning campaign to foster the practice of lifelong learning for
lifelong employability and the campaign will culminate in a
Singapore Learning Festival in August this year.
</P>
<P>
Lee urged workers and employers to put the lifelong learning on
top of their agenda and priority and make lifelong learning their
new mind-set and their way of life so as to derive maximum
benefits.
</P>
<P>
"The need for individuals and businesses to upgrade and change
is becoming more urgent. We must re-invent ourselves and make
great efforts to initiate and implement innovative solutions to
meet the challenges of the New Economy," the minister emphasized.
</P>
<P>
Lee said workers in the brick and mortar companies, especially
the small and medium-sized enterprises, must also upgrade their
skills and capabilities to help their companies innovate and grow
in the New Economy.
</P>
<P>
BERI, a world rating institute, has since 1980 rated Singapore'
s workforce as the world's Number One, taking into account its
legal framework, relative productivity, worker attitude and
technical skills.
</P>
<P>
However, it lags behind Japan and Switzerland in the sub-index
on worker attitude and in terms of technical skills, its ranking
is the eighth, after Japan, Switzerland, the United States, the
Netherlands, Germany, Sweden and Denmark. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
