<HEADLINE> Revenue Collection Up 17.1 Percent in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 1 (Xinhua) -- India's revenue collection went up
to 1.673 trillion rupees (38.9 billion U.S. dollars) in the 1999-
2000 fiscal year, a growth of 17.1 percent over the previous
fiscal, according to the preliminary estimates of the Ministry of
Finance.
</P>
<P>
Minister of State for Finance Dhananjava Kumar said Monday that
the government had expected a growth of 15.1 percent but it had
been overshot by 2 percent. He attributed the better performance
to buoyancy in the economy.
</P>
<P>
The government has set a revenue collection target of 2.03
trillion rupees (47.21 billion dollars) for the 2000-2001 fiscal
year, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said the country's gross domestic product growth during the
1999-2000 fiscal year was estimated at 6.5 percent, adding that it
was a moderate estimate.
</P>
<P>
Industry is claiming a 7-percent actual growth, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
