<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Transportation in China Overburdened on Int'l Labor Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Transportation systems throughout
China are staggering under the weight of countless travelers criss-
crossing the country during the week-long International Labor Day
holiday.
</P>
<P>
Today marked the start of China's first state-approved seven-
day vacation in the spring -- one of the finest periods in the
year for sightseeing.
</P>
<P>
In northeast China's port city of Dalian, a famous seaside
resort, the high number of passengers have caused delays of trains
and ships. Airways, railway departments and ship companies have
had to increase flights, trains and ferries for vacationers
flocking in and out of Dalian.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that the city will receive 300,000 tourists,
while more than 50,000 local residents are leaving for the long
holiday.
</P>
<P>
Southwestern Airlines of China has increased eight flights from
Chengdu City in Sichuan Province to Lhasa in the holiday to enable
more people to travel to Tibet. The airline is usually busy in
July-September period.
</P>
<P>
"The number of tourists going to Tibet during this holiday is 3,
500 more than last year's figure," said Deng Jianli at the Lhasa
office of Southwestern Airlines.
</P>
<P>
And in southwest China's Chongqing Municipality, tickets for
cruises down the Yangtze River were sold out days ago.
</P>
<P>
Baiyun International Airport in south China's Guangzhou City
today handled more than 200 flights with 34,000 passengers, about
10,000 people more than on May 1 last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
