<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rise of Ethnic Minority Officials in Hunan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The number of ethnic minority
officials in central China's Hunan Province has grown by 60
percent in the past seven years, participants at the provincial
ethnic minority working conference which ended here yesterday were
told.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1999, Hunan had 133,000 ethnic minority officials,
a rise of over 50,000 over the figure in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that Hunan has 5.5 million ethnic minority
people, accounting for 8.2 percent of the total provincial
population, while the number of ethnic minority officials accounts
for some 8.82 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
Colleges and universities in Hunan offer special training
classes for ethnic minority officials which have to date trained
over 12,000 people. Among them, 600 have received undergraduate
diplomas and more than 2,000 were granted three-year diplomas.
</P>
</TEXT>
