<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 49th PATA Annual Conference Opens in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The 49th Pacific Asia Travel
Association (PATA) Annual Conference, which is participated by
some 1,300 delegates from 46 countries and regions, opened here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
With the theme of "The Future is Now," the PATA conference is
considered the premier meeting-place for travel and tourism
leaders. Delegates are expected to discuss such topics as
technology, environment and partnership between the public and
private in the tourism industry in the three-day conference.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening ceremony, Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR), said the
conference theme was especially appropriate, with the delegates
demonstrating determination and willingness to accept
responsibility regarding the development and shaping of global
tourism.
</P>
<P>
"The significance of tourism to economies around the world is
enormous," said Tung. "And there is every indication that travel
and tourism will play an increasingly important role in economic
development in the new century."
</P>
<P>
In the case of Hong Kong, the tourism industry contributes
between 4 to 5 percent of the GDP, and more than 10.5 million
visitors to Hong Kong last year helped boost receipts from the
tourism industry to some 53 billion HK dollars (6.8 billion U.S.
dollars), he noted.
</P>
<P>
J. Daniel Burruss, chairman of the PATA, said business
opportunities and solutions that people wouldn't have dreamed of
even a year ago emerge nearly every day at present.
</P>
<P>
"Our industry keeps racing ahead so quickly," said Burruss. "
New technology, e-commerce, space travel -- all of these are
taking shape around us."
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that participants will gain new ideas and
new friendship that propel the tourism business far into the
future.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1951, the PATA is the recognized authority on
Pacific Asia travel and tourism. Its members include nearly 100
government, state and city tourism bodies, and more than 200
travel companies and organizations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
