<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Again Holds up Plan to Transfer Arab Villages: Radio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
is unlikely to submit his plan of handing over three villages on
the outskirts of Jerusalem to the Palestinians for cabinet approval
this week.
</P>
<P>
The plan, in which Abu Dis, Azariya, and Swahara would be handed
over to full Palestinian control in the next few weeks as a
confidence building measure for the two sides to reach a final-
status framework agreement, was originally expected to be discussed
in Wednesday's cabinet meeting, according to Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Minister in Prime Minister's Office Haim Ramon, one of
Barak's closest confidants, confirmed in a interview with Israeli
Army Radio on Sunday the government plan to transfer these
Jerusalem neighborhoods, which currently under Israeli security and
Palestinian civilian control.
</P>
<P>
Ramon's remarks drew immediate fierce verbal attacks from
Israel's rightist parties, with two of Barak's ruling coalition
partners, Yisrael Ba'aliya and National Religious Party, even
threatening to quit the government or to support no-confidence
motions over the issue.
</P>
<P>
It was not the first time since the beginning of this year that
Barak or his confidants suggested the handover, only to withdraw
the plan later due to pressure from the right-wing politicians.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio on Monday cited the failed meeting between Barak
and the ultraorthodox religious Shas party mentor Rabbi Ovadia
Yosef late Sunday night as the main reason for the last-minute
attitude change this time.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was made possible after Barak caved in to Shas'
financial demands on its ailing education network, which is
desperately in need for cash to survive.
</P>
<P>
Barak hoped his gesture to transfer some 10 million shekels
(about 2.5 million U.S. dollars) in advance to save the school
system would ensure the Shas spiritual leader's support for the
handover of the Arab villages and other issues on the Israeli-
Palestinian peace track.
</P>
<P>
An endorsement of Yosef, who has dominant policy-making power in
the Shas party, would guarantee the support of the four Shas
ministers in the cabinet and its pivotal 17 members in the 120-seat
Knesset (Parliament) for future government peace proposals.
</P>
<P>
However, Barak's strategy appeared unsuccessful again. Akiva
Eldar, a columnist for Israel's Ha'aretz daily, wrote in Monday's
edition that Yosef is not about to "give up his guns" so easily at
this stage.
</P>
<P>
"If he agrees in advance to support the peace agreements, what
pistol will have to aim at Barak the next time the coffers of his
institutions empty out?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
As the effort to ensure Shas' support failed, Barak had no other
choices but to withdraw his plan in order not to anger Yisrael
Ba'aliya and National Religious Party pointlessly.
</P>
<P>
Barak reportedly wanted to use these villages as part of "
advance payments" to the Palestinians before the further withdrawal
from the West Bank and Gaza Strip, which is due to happen by June.
</P>
<P>
The negotiation teams from both sides have been holding talks in
Israel's Red Sea resort of Eilat since Sunday, discussing the final
redeployment and all other interim and final-status issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
