<HEADLINE> Nigeria, S.Africa to Offer Troops to UN Mission in Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria and South Africa Sunday
offered to contribute to the proposed United Nations Peace-keeping
Force to be deployed in the Democratic Republic of the Congo
(DRC), according to the News Agency of Nigeria (NAN)on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The offer was highly praised by Organization of African Unity
(OAU) secretary-general Salim Ahmed Salim, who attended a summit
on the DRC conflict, which was also attended by six African
leaders, including President Olusegun Obasanjo, in the Algerian
capital, Algiers.
</P>
<P>
Other African leaders attending the meeting were Thabo Mbeki of
South Africa, Laurent Kabila of DRC, Joaquim Chissano of
Mozambique, Alpha Oumar Konare of Mali and the host, Abdelaziz
Bouteflika.
</P>
<P>
Botswana's former President Ketumile Masire who is charged with
 establishing dialogue among the DRC government, political
opposition and rebels; the Zambian president's representative,
Eric Suwilansi and the UN Secretary-General's aide for DRC, Kamel
Morjane were also at the talks.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after the announcement, Salim told reporters that with
the offers "the momentum has been created for the speedy
deployment of a force."
</P>
<P>
In the statement, the African leaders appealed to the UN
Security Council to embark on the "speedy deployment" of the
peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
Salim said discussions focused on ways to consolidate the
latest cease- fire, which took effect April 14, so that the
Security Council can give the green light to the deployment of a
5,500-strong peacekeeping force authorized in February.
</P>
<P>
The force, comprising 500 military observers and 500 supporting
troops, will be tasked with monitoring the ceasefire and
withdrawal of combatants.  
</P>
</TEXT>
