<HEADLINE> Disputed Peninsula between Nigeria, Cameroon Vulnerable to Ocean Surge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The oil-rich Bakassi Peninsula,
subject of a raging border dispute between Nigeria and Cameroon,
is on the verge of being submerged by the Atlantic Ocean, said
Chairman of the Bakassi Council under the Nigerian government
Emmanuel Etene on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian, a leading Nigerian newspaper, Monday quoted the
official as appealing to Nigerian president that if nothing
urgent is done, the entire Bakassi peninsula, especially Abana,
the council headquarters would be submerged soon.
</P>
<P>
The embankment built by the council, he said, has been
destroyed by the powerful waves while the Federal government is
yet to react to the baseline study on the ocean surge sent to it.
</P>
<P>
The chairman said that between last November and this January,
marine erosion submerged property worth over 100 million naira (1
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Nigeria and its neighboring Cameroon have fought several wars
over the sovereignty of Bakassi. The two countries are currently
entangled in a protracted lawsuit over the ownership of the
peninsula at the Hague international court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
