<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feathered Dinosaurs on Show in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Eight pieces of rare feathered
dinosaur fossils, the Class I national treasures of China, will be
on display at Hong Kong Science Museum from May 2 to June 11,
revealing the evolutionary relationship between dinosaurs and
birds.
</P>
<P>
Being shown for the first time in Asia, all the eight pieces
genuine fossils are the types of feathered dinosaurs found in
China's Liaoning Province and of more than 100 million years old.
</P>
<P>
The pieces to be shown are Sinosauropteryx, the first feathered
dinosaur found in the world; Liaoxiornis, the smallest prehistoric
bird ever known; Caudipteryx, the first dinosaur that possessed
primitive feathers; Confuciusornis, the first bird that possessed
a beak; and Huaxiasaurus, Dromaeosaurus, Protarchaeopteryx and
Changchengornis.
</P>
<P>
There has been a controversy for 130 years as to whether birds
originated from dinosaurs since T. Huxley, a British scholar
proposed in 1870 that blood relationship existed between birds and
theropod dinosaurs.
</P>
<P>
These exquisitely preserved fossils of dinosaurs reveal
different stages in the evolution of the shoulders and forelimbs
of theropod dinosaurs and provide crucial evidence for how
grasping arms were transformed into flying wings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000501.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Sure to Retaliate If Attacked: U.S. DM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 1 ( Xinhua ) -- U.S. Secretary of Defense, William
Cohen warned that Israel will not stand still if attacked by its
neighbors, and "this may lead to a serious confrontation in
Lebanon and other countries."
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Arab daily "Alhayat", published
Monday, Cohen said he believes that the "Syrians are fully aware
that the Israelis will respond to any attacks against them."
</P>
<P>
Cohen quoted the Israeli prime minister, whom he has recently
met with, as saying the "opportunity window between Damascus and
Tel
Aviv is very narrow, and is about to be closed, although it is
still
open."
</P>
<P>
He added that he "was not optimistic about the possible
resumption of talks between the two sides."
</P>
<P>
Regarding the situation in Iraq, Cohen stressed on the
necessity of the continued sanctions on Iraq, saying that "since
they proved to
be positive and fruitful, Saddam Hussein (Iraqi President) is no
longer
a real threat to his neighbors."
</P>
<P>
He said the lifting of sanctions imposed on Iraq depends on
its full compliance with the U.N. resolutions, opening the doors
for
the international inspectors, and releasing the prisoners of war.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. minister advised the Gulf states to acquire the "
potentials of the early warning systems and it is up to them to
take a decision in this respect."
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that it is the right of every Gulf state to "
choose what is suitable for its needs in the context of the kind of
its relations "with Iran and Iraq," affirming that "every country
will adopt a track that serves its interests and security needs."
</P>
<P>
Cohen said the Gulf states hope for better
relations with Tehran, provided it stops seeking the acquisition
of the potentials threatening these countries."
</P>
<P>
Cohen termed as "positive development" the Iranian moves to
stop the trafficking of the Iraqi oil, expressing his country's
wish to have better ties with Iran, urging Tehran to give up its
efforts aimed at hindering the Middle East peace process, refrain
from backing terrorism and attempting to possess weapons of mass
destruction." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
