<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 1 (Xinhua)-- The Australian sharemarket closed
lower Monday ahead of likely interest rate rises both in Australia
and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The Reserve Bank of Australia meet on Tuesday and Wednesday is
tipped to lift rates from 5.75 percent to 6.00 percent.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index downed 13.3 points at 3,071.8 while
the new benchmark S&AMP;P/ASX200 lost 13.8 points to 3,102.0.
</P>
<P>
Among the banks, ANZ's shares declined 40 cents to 11.44
Australian dollars. Westpac dropped 43 cents to 10.50 Australian
dollars, St George dipped 21 cents to 11.14 Australian dollars,
the Commonwealth eased 0.7 of a cent to 26.073 Australian dollars
and NAB ended up 3.1 cents to 23.491 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Resource stocks were mostly lower, BHP went down 38 cents to 18.
06 Australian dollars, WMC fell 16 cents to 6.95 Australian
dollars, Rio Tinto slumped 16.3 cents to 25.60 Australian dollars
and North surrendered 7.7 cents to 2.868 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
News Corp prevented the sharemarket from downing further. It
ordinary shares climbed almost two percent, or 39.4 cents, to 22.
14 Australian dollars while its preferred scrip shot up 3.5
percent, or 66.2 cents, to 19.082 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 449.68 million shares worth 1.068 billion
Australian dollars (619.44 million U.S. dollars). There were 479
rising stocks, 953 fell and 444 were steady. 
</P>
</TEXT>
