<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian PM to Meet With Arafat in Gaza </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister John
Howard is scheduled to travel to Gaza on Monday to hold talks with
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat mainly on Israeli-Palestinian
peace talks, Israeli foreign ministry officials said.
</P>
<P>
Howard, who arrived here last Saturday on a four-day visit, met
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak on Sunday, who briefed him on the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Australian foreign minister said he sees special
opportunities for peace at this time.
</P>
<P>
"Australia can, at a diplomatic level, encourage and support the
initiatives of the principal players", he said, adding that this is
what he intends to do during his talks with Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Barak said that the Palestinians must have territorial congruity
in order to separate them with Israel.
</P>
<P>
In an apparent response to criticism that his intended transfer
of three villages east of Jerusalem to the Palestinian control
might weaken Israel's control of united Jerusalem as its capital,
Barak said one should not confuse the villages Azariya and Abu-Dis
as being part of Jerusalem towards which all Jews pray.
</P>
<P>
Barak's office revealed on Sunday that the government planned to
hand over Abu Dis, Azariya and Swahara to full Palestinian control
in the next few weeks, as a good-will gesture to the Palestinians
in advance of the final Israeli troops withdrawal from the West
Bank and Gaza Strip, which is due to take place by June.
</P>
<P>
The move, however, has sparked severe criticism from the
rightists.
</P>
<P>
Barak noted that no one is talking about transferring to the
Palestinians any territory that they do not already control, but
the transfer of 3 percent of the 39.2 percent already under
Palestinian rule from area B to area A. The good-will gesture,
however, has been turned down by the Palestinian side on fears that
the gesture would sacrifice a larger territorial compromise in the
final status agreement.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Sunday, Howard received an honorary doctorate from
Bar-Ilan University in recognition of his friendship toward the
Jewish people. He also held talks with other Israeli officials
during the visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
