<HEADLINE> hke050131-- Manila Reaffirms Commitment to Peace Process with MILF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government reaffirmed
Monday its commitment to pursuing the peace process with the Moro
Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) amid reports that the group has
indefinitely suspended formal peace talks with the government.
</P>
<P>
Secretary Orlando Mercado of the Department of National Defense
at the same time reminded the MILF that the government has a sworn
duty to ensure public safety, and thus, will not tolerate any
criminal or terrorist act by some of wayward MILF members.
</P>
<P>
"We believe in the peace talks. But we will not allow some MILF
members to continue with their illegal acts and recruitment of new
members while the peace process is ongoing," Mercado said in a
radio interview.
</P>
<P>
The MILF pulled out from the scheduled resumption of peace
talks on May 16 after the fighting broke out last week in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Government troops are locked in battle for the third day on
Monday against 1,000 MILF rebels occupying a vital highway in
Matanog, Maguindanao province in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Mercado accused the MILF of starting the fighting, saying the
military had to act because of the MILF's occupation of the
strategic highway linking several provinces in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
The government and the MILF signed a ceasefire agreement in
1997 as prelude to the opening of formal peace talks to find a
lasting solution to the Mindanao conflict.
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Joseph Estrada has set a deadline to sign
a peace agreement with the MILF by June 30 this year.
</P>
<P>
However, the MILF has asked the president to reconsider his
decision, saying there should be no imposition of deadline to find
a lasting solution to the long-drawn Mindanao problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
