<HEADLINE> hke050132-- 4 Indonesian Military Officers Grilled Over East Timor Mayhem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 1 (Xinhua) -- As a further step of investigation
into an alleged human rights abuse in East Timor, four Indonesian
Military (TNI) and police officer were questioned on Monday by
prosecutors of the Attorney General's Office (AGO).
</P>
<P>
They are Brig. Gen. (police) Timbul Silaen, former East Timor
police chief; Maj. Gen. Adam Damiri, former Udayana Military
Commander overseeing East Timor; Brig. Gen. Tono Suratman and Col.
Noer Muis, the last two chiefs of the Wiradharma District Military
Command in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
The fours were questioned at the AGO as witnesses in the case
of a human rights abuse in the breakaway province of East Timor in
1999.
</P>
<P>
"The four officers are grilled over their possible involvement
in human rights abuse in East Timor. But they are questioned as
witnesses. I don't know who is the suspect in this case, or who
will be the suspect," said Mohammad Assegaf, a lawyer who
accompanying the officers in the course of the questioning.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the statement of Attorney General Marzuki
Darusman that the trial will begin by mid-May or late May, Assegaf
said, adding that such a trial will still face trouble as the
country has yet had a human rights bill.
</P>
<P>
In late January, the National Commission on Human Rights (
Komnas HAM) recommended as many as 33 people, including former TNI
chief Gen. Wiranto, were allegedly involved in what it said as a
crime against humanity in East Timor and urged the AGO to make
further probe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
