<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Posts 0.56 Percent Inflation in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of the Central Bureau of
Statistic (BPS) Sugito Suwito announced here Monday that Indonesia
posted a 0.56 percent inflation in April, higher than the figure
in March which reached minus 0.45 percent.
</P>
<P>
He said that inflation rate during January-April 2000 reached 1.
5 percent.
</P>
<P>
"The rise of the inflation figure in April is due to the
increase of all consumer price index but food price index," Suwito
told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
He said that of the seven groups of consumer goods mentioned in
the consumer price index, six groups were in the grip of inflation,
while the one another namely, foods group, was recorded to have
undergone deflation by minus 1.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
"The inflation-hit six groups included food processed, drinks,
cigarette and tobacco 2.41 percent, housing 1.17 percent, clothing
0.17 percent, healthy 1.1 percent, education, recreation and
sports 0.97 percent while transportation and communication 1.62
percent,"Suwito added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000501.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Keeps Bombing Syrian Airfield Mock-ups in Training </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Israel Air Force (IAF) has been
bombing life-size mock-ups of Syrian airports in training in the
past few years, an IAF official publication revealed on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The two airfield models were constructed at an IAF training
ground deep in the Negev Desert in south Israel, with true-to-life
runaways, approach routes, useless A-4 Skyhawks fighter jets as
targets, and underground hangars, according to Israel's Air Force
Magazine.
</P>
<P>
The magazine, which hit the newsstands on Monday, also leaked
that all the airport infrastructures were copied from the spy
satellite photos in order to create a life-like battle atmosphere
and better simulate the difficulty the fighter pilots may face in a
real war field.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the airport mock-ups had been in existence
for years, with nearly all fighter pilots in the air force
undergoing training there several times.
</P>
<P>
This report made military strategists here wonder why the IAF
publicized the bombing training on "Syrian airports", even in
virtual reality, at such a time while the talks between Israel and
Syria are in deep stalemate since January and while Israel plans to
withdraw its army from south Lebanon in July.
</P>
<P>
The mystery was redoubled as the report mentioned other airfield
models in IAF training, which were also reproduced from photos of
airports in other Middle East countries, but their identities have
been kept classified.
</P>
<P>
According to at least one version of the speculation, Israeli
army officers are showing their strength and determination to
retaliate Syria in case that Syria's ally in Lebanon foot-drags the
Israeli troops withdrawal from the security zone.
</P>
<P>
In March, Israeli cabinet approved the pullout from the buffer
zone, which Israel created in 1985 with a self-claimed aim to
prevent guerrilla attacks against its north, due to great pressure
from home and abroad against its continuing occupation of Lebanon
territories.
</P>
<P>
However, IAF officers believed that Syria is afraid that the
redeployment will remove the most powerful bargaining chip from its
hand in the talks with Israel to regain control of its Golan
Heights, a strategic plateau which Israel has been occupying since
the 1967 Middle East War.
</P>
<P>
The difference over the Golan had kept the Israeli-Syrian talks
in deadlock since January after two fruitless rounds of talks in
the United States earlier.
</P>
<P>
When the last effort to revive the talks, a summit meeting
between U.S. President Bill Clinton and Syrian President Hafez al-
Assad in Geneva in March, failed to accomplish its mission, there
were even panic reports in Israeli media that Syria was brewing a
major attack operation against Israel.
</P>
<P>
Quoting an IAF officer, the Air Force Magazine reported on
Monday that the training on Syrian airfield models is following the
IAF traditional strategy to achieve air superiority by attacking
the enemy's runaways.
</P>
<P>
This is a priority target in today's battle plans, the magazine
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
