<HEADLINE> Israel's First Spaceman to Go Up Next Spring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Israel's first spaceman is
scheduled to fly into outer space within the United States' shuttle
Columbia by mid 2001, Israel's Air Force Magazine revealed on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Colonel Ilan Ramon was chose by American's National
Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) as a crew on the 107th
flight of the shuttle, which is due to take off next April or May,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Ramon, a former accomplished fighter pilot in Israel Air Force
who has been in training for space mission at Johnson Space Center
in Texas since 1998, once was expected to be lifted off in that
year for commemorating Israel's 50th Independence Day. However, he
had to wait for more time for ending his training.
</P>
<P>
The major task of his first mission is performing experiments,
including a project master-planned by 35 Israeli eight-grade pupils
from the Kiryat Motzhkin's Ort school.
</P>
<P>
The project, code-named "a chemical garden", is aimed to observe
the growth of seeds in space and solve a yet unanswered question -
why sprouts grow upwards on Earth.
</P>
<P>
Quoted by the magazine, Ramon said: "This is the first step in
involving more of the Israeli establishment in the space program
and it exposes the youth to an exciting field." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
