<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 14 killed, Over 230 Injured in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, May 1 (Xinhua) -- At least 14 government soldiers were
killed and 236 others injured in fierce fighting with the Tamil
rebels in northern Jaffna Peninsula of Sri Lanka on Sunday, a
defense spokesman said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman M. Indunil said during daytime on Sunday fierce
fighting erupted in northern Pallai town in north of Elephant Pass,
ahead of the main defense line now being constructed after the
vacation of Elephant Pass base.
</P>
<P>
The troops manning positions in Ittavil in northern of Pallai
town, were engaged by the rebels from north and south at the same
time.
</P>
<P>
The troops were forced to withdraw from Vempotukerni with a
large number of casualties. Similarly the troops deployed in
Palopullai and Pallai also withdrew after receiving heavy
casualties, he said.
</P>
<P>
Indunil added that the troops are now deployed in their
delaying positions in area north of Pallai town ahead of the main
defense line.
</P>
<P>
The fall of Pallai to the rebels puts added pressure on the
government troops, which are batting to hold Jaffna Peninsula
after losing strategic Elephant Pass, the gateway to the Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
Pallai lies about 45 kilometers south of Jaffna, the main city
on the northern Jaffna peninsula which recaptured by government
troops in May 1996.
</P>
<P>
The rebels, who have been fighting for a separate Tamil
homeland in the north and east of the country, are trying to
recapture the northern Jaffna Peninsula -- their former stronghold,
after they captured the key Elephant pass army base last weekend.
</P>
</TEXT>
