<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zanzibari Opposition Leader Joins Presidential Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The Secretary general of
Zanzibar's main opposition Civic United Front (CUF) Seif Shariff
Hamad Sunday collected nomination forms to aspire for the
presidency on the spice islands in the forthcoming general
elections scheduled for next October.
</P>
<P>
According to Tanzanian newspapers report on Monday, shortly
after collecting the forms at the CUF branch at Mtoni, Zanzibar at
a function which was also attended by senior CUF officials, Hamad
told reporters that his decision was influenced by mass support he
received from fellow Zanzibaris.
</P>
<P>
"CUF supporters have appealed all along for me to join the
presidential race. Therefore, I'm just fulfilling the wishes of
the people," he was quoted as saying, adding that his chances in
the polls are high.
</P>
<P>
Hamad becomes the first Zanzibari to announce formally his
intention to run for the Isles top position. No one has come
forward to join the presidential race from within the ranks of
ruling Chama Cha Mapinduzi (CCM) in Zanzibar.
</P>
<P>
The opposition Secretary General is expected to return the
nomination forms on Wednesday, the deadline for the exercise.
</P>
<P>
Hamad, who was Zanzibar Chief Minister from 1984 to 1988,
stressed that he is ready to form a government of national unity
to enhance solidarity in the Isles.
</P>
<P>
The CUF claims President Salmin Amour's ruling CCM party rigged
October 1995 elections in the Zanzibar region in the Indian Ocean
off mainland Tanzania, in which Hamad lost by less than 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Though it joined with Tanganyika to form the nation of Tanzania
in 1964, Zanzibar is a semiautonomous state with its own
government and parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
