<HEADLINE> Nigerian Senate Urges for Mutual Respect Within Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Senate President Chuba
Okadigbo Sunday underscored the need for mutual respect among the
three arms of government to avert political crisis, which may
jeopardize the country's nascent democracy.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian, a leading Nigerian newspaper, Monday quoted
Okadigbo as saying that the on-going moves to reconcile the
executive with the legislature would fail unless the relationship
between them was based on mutual respect.
</P>
<P>
The only way out of the on-going standoff between the two
government arms was for each of them to operate within its limit,
he said after another closed-door meeting with President Olusegun
Obasanjo at the weekend in the country's capital Abuja.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the tension generated in the senate over reported
moves to impeach him, Okadigbo said "I will remain in charge in
spite of any future attempt." 
</P>
</TEXT>
