<DOCNO> XIE20000501.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Electricity Consumers to Pay More </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Electricity consumers in Kenya will
pay an extra 717 million shillings (9.7 million U.S. dollars) for
April to the Kenya Power and Lighting Company and fuel
adjustment costs, the East African weekly reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The huge payment is attributed to the drop in the Kenya
shilling, rising fuel cost and increased reliance on thermal
sources of energy in the face of prolonged drought.
</P>
<P>
"We have to step up the volume of fuel power generation when
the three main hydro electric power dams experienced low water
level leading to power rating last September," said James
Macharia, communications officer of the Kenya Power and Lighting
Company.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Masinga, Kamburu and Turkwell reservoirs are the
main sources of water for hydro-power generation in the country,
adding that they were hit by excess capacity following below
normal rains last year.
</P>
<P>
The increase in thermal production from 88.3 million kwh in
1999 August to 145.6 million kwh in March this year forced the
utility providers to slap a fuel cost adjustment for electricity
generation, Macharia explained.
</P>
<P>
Another factor for payment increase, he said, is the drop in
the value of the shilling from 67 shillings to the dollar in 1999
August to 75 shillings to the dollar in March this year, which
led to an increase in foreign exchange adjustment.
</P>
<P>
The two charges combined will cost electricity consumers 7.9
million dollars in one month alone if the level of 388 million
kwh supplied in March was met, he said.
</P>
<P>
Macharia said the electricity suppliers is optimistic that dam
levels will return to normal with the long rains so that the
reliance on thermal power generation, the cause to high fuel
adjustment cost, is minimized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
