<DOCNO> XIE20000501.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> E. African Nations Unite to Fight Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Ten East African countries have
adopted a plan to monitor crime and enhance information exchange
with the International Police Organization (Interpol), the East
African weekly reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The plan, worked out at a meeting in Kenya's capital Nairobi
last week, will be implemented by the respective countries with
aid from the newly- established Interpol sub-regional bureau in
Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from Kenya, Uganda, Tanzania, Burundi, Rwanda,
Eritrea, Ethiopia, Seychelles, Djibouti and Sudan attended the
meeting last week and agreed that intelligence information from
the respective countries will be exchanged through the Interpol
bureau to create harmony and cooperation in security matters.
</P>
<P>
Peter Kimundi, head of the Interpol East African sub-regional
bureau, said that no country can win the war against crime
singlehanded, which means they have to use a common front to
eradicate crime in their respective countries.
</P>
<P>
The Nairobi meeting came on the heels of an international small
arms conference held here last month to discuss ways and means of
curbing the proliferation of small arms in East Africa and the
Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
According to Interpol officials, plans are underway to install
a new Interpol telecommunications system which will improve access
to the general secretariat database in Lyons, France, and
information interchange between states.
</P>
<P>
At present, the Interpol has three sub-regional bureaux in
Africa, one in Nairobi for East Africa, one in Zimbabwe's capital
Harare for southern Africa and one in Abidjan, the capital of Cote
d'Ivoire, for west Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
