<HEADLINE> Study: Child Workers In Poor Condition in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 1 (Xinhua) -- A study, published on the eve of the
May 1 International Labor Day, shows that Turkish child labor are
working under poor conditions, reported Turkish Daily News on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Some 44.4 percent of the 200 children working at the Pendik
automobile factory are under 15, and all of them are under 18,
according to the survey, conducted by the Turkish Confederation of
Employers' Unions and the International Labor Organization.
</P>
<P>
Some of the children even start working as young as 12
years old. Half of the children, who are from very poor families,
said
they would go back to school if they had the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
Health tests, carried out on the children, showed that 94
percent of them had developed breathing problems, bronchitis and
ear infections as well as many other infections and illnesses.
Close to 60 percent of them had had inoculations while at school.
</P>
<P>
The survey also revealed that 97 percent of the children work up
to 14 hours a day but do not get any overtime pay.
</P>
<P>
Some 44.4 percent of the children have had minor or major
accidents in the workplace involving being accidentally riveted and
losing their fingers or hands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
