<HEADLINE> E. African, U.S. Troops on Military Exercise in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Rehabilitation of the Malindi and
Hoda district hospitals in Coast Province, eastern Kenya, is among
the first activities of a joint military training exercise by East
African troops and U.S. marines, local newspapers reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The exercise, which was set to start for three weeks from now,
will deploy the troops to a stimulated strife-stricken country
nicknamed Galana to test their peace-keeping support operations
skills.
</P>
<P>
The joint military training, co-named "Natural Fire 2000", is
joined by about 3,000 soldiers from Kenya, Uganda, Tanzanian and
the United States.
</P>
<P>
Over 1,000 soldiers from the United States will participate in
the training.
</P>
<P>
Francis Nthenge, director of the joint information bureau, said
on Sunday that the rehabilitation of medical facilities was part
of the troops' humanitarian activities for the two-phase training
in the next two months.
</P>
<P>
During the training, he said, the soldiers would also give free
 treatment to livestock as part of their veterinary medical
assistance programs.
</P>
<P>
"The exercise aims at imparting a better understanding of the
complexity of coordinating a multi-faceted peace support operation
right from conflict prevention, management, disaster relief and
humanitarian civil assistance,"
</P>
<P>
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
