<HEADLINE> Zambia to Amend Electoral Act </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Zambia will amend its Electoral Act
to include representatives of political parties and other interest
groups, the Times of Zambia newspaper reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Bobby Bwalya, Electoral Commission (EC) chairman, was quoted as
saying in an interview in Lusaka that it will also introduce
continuous voter registration in readiness for next year's
presidential and general elections.
</P>
<P>
The Commission would soon present a budget to the government
for the forthcoming elections as preliminary preparations gain
ground, he said.
</P>
<P>
All that is required now is to amend the Electoral Act in the
next session of the parliament, the chairman said, adding that the
parliament is likely to resume its sittings in July or August.
</P>
<P>
"We want registration of voters to be a continuous process. It
is only a question of logistics and availability of money," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the commission wanted to ensure there were sufficient
materials in place so that the registration exercise went on
without hiccups once it commenced.
</P>
<P>
A structure of handling elections was already in place, Bwalya
said, explaining that a new dimension added to the process was
allowing school head teachers, district police chiefs and
principals of colleges to be returning officers.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the concept of free and fair elections has
always been provided for under the Electoral Act. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
