<DOCNO> XIE20000501.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia to Benefit from EU-SADC Mining Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Zambia is to benefit from the new
European Union (EU)-Southern African Development Community (SADC)
technical assistance agreement for the region's small-scale mining
operations to improve productivity, an EU spokesperson has said.
</P>
<P>
The technical assistance program, which comes in the wake of
the anticipated release next month of 35 million euros (about 32
million U.S. dollars) by the EU for onward lending to the Zambian
small-scale mining sector, would run for at least three years, the
spokesperson was quoted by Monday's Times of Zambia newspaper as
saying.
</P>
<P>
In response to a press query, the spokesperson said the new
agreement would allow the region's small-scale mining operations
get exposed to new technology in the mining of gemstones and other
precious stones.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesperson, a significant development in the
new agreement was that technical assistance to operators in the
SADC small- scale mining sector would continue alongside the
dissemination of information on the development of the regional
mining sector.
</P>
<P>
The same technical assistance would also be extended to the
African Developers and Prospectors' Association and the African
Dimension Stone Association.
</P>
<P>
The project, whose agreement was reached ahead of the
forthcoming EU/ SADC mining sector forum scheduled for Lusaka
later this year, would be associated with the Center for the
Development of Industry.
</P>
<P>
The European Investment Bank would assess the type of projects
before releasing funds for providing technical assistance to the
operators.
</P>
<P>
A detailed document, which includes a recent mineral
prospecting study on the region's mining environment and its
potential, would be available at the forthcoming forum expected to
start in November.
</P>
<P>
The Lusaka forum would be an opportunity for the SADC
small-scale mining operators to present proposals to serious
investors from Europe, Asia, the United States and Australia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
