<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rise Sharply in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices rose sharply across the
board in Tokyo Monday on expectations that new investment trusts
or mutual funds to be launched this month will actively buy stocks.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange surged 429.38 points, or 2.39
percent from last Friday's close to end at 18,403.08.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, advanced 46.36 points or 2.81 percent to 1,
695.23.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section decreased to 584.87 million
shares from last Friday's 613.01 million shares, with investors
waiting to see how Wall Street will move during Japan's "Golden
Week" holiday season, traders said.
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo stock market is open only on Monday and Tuesday this
week.
</P>
<P>
The gain in the Nasdaq, combined with the U.S. dollar's advance
to the 108 yen level, boosted Japan's export-oriented high-tech
issues, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Information and telecom issues were strong, while rubber makers,
wholesalers and drug makers also drew active buying.
</P>
<P>
The paper and pulp and the glass and ceramics industries were
the only losers in the main section's 33 business sectors.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, gainers overwhelmed
losers 1,088 to 231, with issues closing unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000501.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lakers Hit First Bump In NBA Playoffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 30 (Xinhua) -- The mighty Los Angeles Lakers
Sunday hit their first bump on the road on many observers expect
to be a stroll to the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
Shaquille O'Neal lost his shooting touch. Kobe Bryant was
slowed by foul trouble. Suddenly, the mighty Los Angeles Lakers
were not invincible.
</P>
<P>
After being manhandled for two games in Los Angeles, the Kings,
spurred on by a noisy sellout home crowd, went on a stunning 14-0
fourth-quarter tear to pull off a 99-91 win.
</P>
<P>
In the final period, Predrag Stojakovic and Tony Delk came off
the Kings bench and teamed with Chris Webber to rally Sacramento
to victory.
</P>
<P>
Stojakovic scored 10 of his 19 points in the fourth and Delk
had nine of his 11, while grabbing four offensive rebounds. Webber
finished with 29 points, 14 rebounds and eight assists for the
Kings, who stay alive in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
O'Neal had 21 points and 17 rebounds, but went 8-for-22 from
the field and 5-for-14 from the foul line. Bryant, who picked up
his fourth foul early in the third period, had 16 of his 35 points
in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
"I'm a believer in reality and the reality is that we just beat
a good team and they're going to be mad when they come in Tuesday,
" said Webber, "so we just better be ready to play."
</P>
<P>
The Lakers won the first two games by comfortable margins in
Los Angeles. Game 4 in the best-of-five series is Tuesday night at
Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
The Kings still face a harrowing task as they try to upset the
best team in the NBA this season. Only 12 teams have rallied to
win a series after trailing 2-0, and none since the Houston
Rockets in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The scenario is familiar for the Lakers. In each of the
previous three seasons, Los Angeles has won the first two games of
its first-round series, then lost Game 3 and wrapped up the series
in four games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
