<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey to Adopt Navigation System in Straits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. company Lockheed Maritime
Overseas will undertake construction of the Turkish Straits Vessel
Traffic Management and Information System, reported Turkish Daily
News on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The company won the 20.4 million U.S. dollar contract in a bid
process conducted by the Turkish Maritime Undersecretariat.
</P>
<P>
The contract entails the building of an operation center with
eight towers, each 15 meters tall in Bosphorus Strait. An
additional five towers are to be built in the Dardanelles Strait.
</P>
<P>
Turkey lies between Asia and Europe, being surrounded by three
seas of the Mediterranean, the Aegean and the Black. The two
continents are separated by straits, consisting from southwest to
northeast, of the Dardanelles, the Sea of Marmara and the
Bosphorus.
</P>
<P>
State Minister Ramazan Mirzaoglu told the cabinet that an
average of 50,000 ships a year navigate the 325 kilometer waterway
between the Aegean and Black seas.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said, some 2,500 unregulated passenger and
various services ships traverse the channels each day carrying over
1 million passengers.
</P>
<P>
As ship dimensions continue to grow and even outgrow the
unchanging geography of the waterway, the risk of accidents
increases, which is why such navigation and information system is
so important, the minister explained.
</P>
<P>
The system will utilize radar, meteorological and oceanographic
systems as well as satellite information systems and day and night
cameras. Ships which previously operated as if they were the only
vessels on the water will now be made aware of each others'
presence, thus reducing the risk of near-misses, collisions and
groundings.
</P>
<P>
In 1999 some 82 million metric tons of hazardous material were
transported through the Bosphorus and some 95 million tons through
the Dardanelles, said the minister. The majority of this cargo was
crude oil, but other chemical products and liquefied petroleum gas
were also carried. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
