<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-Japanese Project to Upgrade Saline Soil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, May 1 (Xinhua) -- A Sino-Japanese cooperative project
has been signed here under which Japanese Agro-scientists will
cooperate with their Chinese counterparts to improve the quality
of saline soil in north China's Shanxi province.
</P>
<P>
Japan will provide about 120 million Japanese yen's worth of
apparatuses, devices and materials needed for the project, and
Japanese experts in the field will also be sent to work in the
project while some Chinese participators will receive related
training in Japan.
</P>
<P>
Implementation of the project is focused on spreading a special
fertilizer developed by a Japanese expert who has made numerous
field trips to Shanxi since 1996. The fertilizer, after having
been experimented with for two consecutive years, proved to be
effective in improving the saline soil and greatly raising its
grain yields.
</P>
<P>
Shanxi is a province with large areas of saline soil, which
could add up to 300,000 hectares in total.  
</P>
</TEXT>
