<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Economic Ministers' Retreat Opens in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, May 1 (Xinhua) -- A retreat meeting of economic
ministers of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN)
opened here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN Economic Ministers (AEM) Retreat, the first of its
kind held in Myanmar, will focus on "East Asia Economic
Cooperation" declared by an informal ASEAN summit in Manila last
November in review of lessons to be drawn from the Asian economic
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony of the AEM retreat, Lt. Gen.
Khin Nyunt, first secretary of the Myanmar State Peace and
Development Council, warned that although most of the Asian
countries hit by the crisis are now at varying levels of economic
recovery, there remain many economic challenges and uncertainties
facing ASEAN and there are social concerns all requiring long-term
sustainable solutions.
</P>
<P>
Khin Nyunt, who is also chairman of Myanmar's ASEAN Steering
Committee, emphasized the importance of implementing the Hanoi
Plan of Action and the Bold Measures adopted at the ASEAN Summit
held in Hanoi in December 1998.
</P>
<P>
He noted the growing awareness in recent years among ASEAN and
East Asian countries, particularly China, Japan and South Korea,
that they share a common destiny.
</P>
<P>
He added that the adoption of the Joint Statement on East Asia
Cooperation at the Third ASEAN Informal Summit in Manila last
November bears testimony to the commitment by ASEAN and these
countries to enhance interaction and develop closer linkages.
</P>
<P>
He expressed Myanmar's appreciation for the support and
cooperation extended by all three dialogue partners during the
recent economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Regarding Myanmar's outlook towards ASEAN, he said the future
of Myanmar and Southeast Asia cannot be separated and that an
ASEAN without Myanmar will not be an ASEAN in its true sense.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated Myanmar's commitment that his country will never
become an obstacle or hindrance to ASEAN and will instead be of
great asset to the regional grouping with the emergence of the
full economic potentials of the nation.
</P>
<P>
The AEM retreat will be followed by a meeting with their
counterparts from three East Asia dialogue partners -- China,
Japan and South Korea -- on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
At the AEM plus 3 meeting, agenda items on information
technology, trade and investment and electronic commerce, Mekong
Basin development, human resources development, agriculture,
industry and tourism will be discussed.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Cambodia, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia,
Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
</TEXT>
