<HEADLINE> S.Lanka's Tamil Rebels Overrun Northern Pallai Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Tamil rebels have
claimed they took Pallai town in the north of the country and
established control over a large area in the Thenmarachchi sector
of Jaffna Peninsula, reports reaching here said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The rebels Sunday overran the massive military base at Pallai,
about 15 km north of Elephant Pass, and also took control of the
town's surrounding villages, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The fall of Pallai by the rebels puts added pressure on the
government troops, which are battling to hold Jaffna Peninsula
after losing the strategic Elephant Pass, the gateway to the
Peninsula, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
There was no immediate official reaction but military sources
here privately admitted that government troops had faced severe
attacks at Pallai and may have withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
Pallai lies about 45 km south of Jaffna, the main city on the
northern Jaffna peninsula which was recaptured by government
troops in May 1996.
</P>
<P>
The reports added that the government was seeking urgent arms
supplies to check the rebels' latest advance.
</P>
<P>
President Chandrika Kumaratunga Friday said the rebels had
rejected all peace overtures, leaving her no option but to try and
defeat them in battlefields.
</P>
<P>
The rebels, who have been fighting for a separate Tamil
homeland in the north and east of the country, are trying to
recapture their former stronghold of Jaffna Peninsula after they
captured the key Elephant Pass army base last weekend. 
</P>
</TEXT>
