<HEADLINE> 37 Legionnaires' Cases Confirmed in Australia's State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Another 8 cases were confirmed as
legionnaires' in Australia's Victorian state Monday, bringing to
37 the number of confirmed cases.
</P>
<P>
According to health officials, a further 32 people were
suspected to have the deadly disease.
</P>
<P>
The death toll remained at two.
</P>
<P>
The outbreak has been blamed on water cooling towers at
Melbourne's new aquarium, visited by almost all those suffering
the disease in mid-April.
</P>
<P>
In Australia's worst-ever outbreak of the disease at Wollongong
in New South Wales in 1987, there were 44 cases and a total of 10
people died.
</P>
<P>
The latest outbreak threw the residents of the state's capital
city Melbourne into panic. Staff have refused to work at the
Melbourne Aquarium while a full investigation takes place.
</P>
<P>
Members of the Construction, Forestry, Mining and Energy Union,
who have been putting finishing touches, such as ramps at the
tourist attraction, walked off the job on Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
An official from the union's health and safety unit insisted
all it's members who were employed over the exposure period be
given full medical monitoring. No work would be done at the
aquarium until medical results and a formal investigation into the
area were completed, he was quoted by Australian Associated Press
as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
