<HEADLINE> IT Production Urged in New Zealand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, May 1 (Xinhua) -- A New Zealand professor has
warned that New Zealand is falling behind the global push in
information technology.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with New Zealand Infotech Weekly, which came
out Monday, Auckland University's professor of information systems
Michael Myers said New Zealanders "know how to use information
technology but have few clues on producing it."
</P>
<P>
"We're very good at using technology but when it comes to
producing technology we're not doing well at all," he said.
</P>
<P>
Compared to Singapore, Israel, and Finland, which have
developed significant IT production and export industries with the
help of government intervention, Myers said, "New Zealand's export
of IT is tiny.
</P>
<P>
"If we, as a country, want to maintain our standard of living,
it seems to me essential that we move into the hi-tech area," he
added.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand must do its best to fully exploit technology
production to boost the economy, Myers stressed.
</P>
<P>
"Information technology is ideal for a country like New Zealand,
"he said.
</P>
<P>
The Auckland University's professor urged the New Zealand
government to actively encourage more research and development in
Information technology. 
</P>
