<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Thai Banks Face Tough Challenges By Yang Qingchuan, Huang Yong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The state and private Thai banks are
now confronted with tough challenges as former compeers became
foreign-controlled competitors and more fellows are falling into
the hands of foreign banks.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, four of the 13 Thai commercial banks have been sold
to foreign buyers -- Nakornthon Bank to Britain's Standard
Chartered Bank, Radanasin Bank to United Overseas Bank of
Singapore, Bank of Asia to ABN-AMRO Bank of Holland, and Thai Danu
Bank to Development Bank of Singapore.
</P>
<P>
And that is not the end of the story. Recently, The London-
based Hongkong and Shanghai Banking Corporation (HSBC) has agreed
with the central bank of Thailand in principle to buy 75 percent
of stake in the Thai-owned Bangkok Metropolitan Bank (BMB). Siam
City Bank, another Thai bank, is on the auction block, waiting for
the foreign buyer.
</P>
<P>
The government has reiterated that some of the Thai banks have
to be sold off as it is impossible to revive the banking system
with local capital and manpower.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Thai central bank governor Chatu Mongol said the
government preferred to retain as many Thai banks as possible, but
the Thai banks' survival depended on whether they can adjust to
compete against foreign banks and "mixed-blood" competitors.
</P>
<P>
With the government's bank-selling policy determined, the
remaining 7 Thai commercial banks now have to compete with not
only 21 branches of foreign banks in Thailand, but also the "mixed
blood" banks -- the foreign-controlled former nationalized or
private Thai banks.
</P>
<P>
In the view of many Thai banking analysts, those "mixed-blood"
banks have considerable edges over their Thai counterparts.
</P>
<P>
As former Thai-owned banks, the "mixed-blood" banks have
established branches across the country, and will be improved
largely in management and technology by their foreign masters,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
A more flexible rate adjustment system and the smaller amount
of bad loans also give the "mixed-blood" competitors a good
position.
</P>
<P>
As the situation is getting worse, the Thai banks have decided
to carry out strategies for their own survival.
</P>
<P>
According to a senior executive of the Bangkok Bank, the
flagship of Thai banks, the Thai banks are now trying hard to
improve their technology, manpower and management to meet the
international standards.
</P>
<P>
Recently, many Thai banks have enhanced service in stores and
supermarkets, offering special service in holidays, promoting
young employees, focusing on non-interest income and taking
measures to prevent the bad loans.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts said that while the reality is hard for the Thai
banks, it can also stimulate them to greater efforts to improve
themselves, thus benefiting the whole banking reform process of
Thailand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000501.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Marks May Day With Rallies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka is marking International
Labor Day Monday with rallies and demonstrations islandwide amidst
tight security precautions.
</P>
<P>
May Day celebrations are traditionally a show of strength by
various political parties in the country. There are usually
marches and processions through the streets, and public meetings
are held under the banners of different political parties.
</P>
<P>
At least 19 rallies and seven demonstrations are planned for
Monday by major political parties and trade unions, marking the
first May Day of the new millennium at different venues in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Five rallies and four demonstrations will be held in the
capital city Colombo, local media sources said.
</P>
<P>
However, the Sri Lankan Freedom Party (SLFP), the main ruling
party, has decided not to hold a rally and processions as a mark
of respect to heroes, the fallen and injured in fighting against
the Tamil rebels in the north of the country recently.
</P>
<P>
And President Chandrika Kumaratunga, who is deputy chairman of
the party, has requested all SLFP party organizers not to hold any
meetings, processions or ceremonies in connection with May Day
this year and to utilize all funds thus saved for the welfare of
the families of the members of the government soldiers who died in
the war and those injured in action.
</P>
<P>
The May Day rally organized by the People's Alliance's
constituent parties -- Sri Lankan Sama Samaja party, the Communist
Party, the Democratic Janatha Vimukthi Party and the Sri Lankan
Mahajana Paksaya -- will be held at the Campbell Park Monday
afternoon. Their demonstration will start at noon.
</P>
<P>
The main opposition United National Party has opted to hold its
demonstration and rally in Nuwara Eliya, Capital of Central
Province.
</P>
<P>
A wide range of other smaller parties and trade unions are also
due to demonstrate for Monday's celebrations and rally in Colombo
or other places islandwide, according to local press reports
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Colombo put the maximum security alert Sunday night as
preparations for Monday's celebrations went on. At least 7,000
policemen and soldiers are deployed to beef up security in the
whole city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
