<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tiger Found Above 3,000 Meters in Bhutan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Nepali wildlife researchers have
successfully caught a tiger in their cameras at an elevation of 3,
000 meters in central Bhutan's ThrumsingLa National Park, The
Kathmandu Post reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first photographic evidence supporting the
presence of a Royal Bengal Tiger at such an high altitude," the
English daily quoted Dr. Yonzon, a wildlife expert in Kathmandu,
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The tiger was photographed on April 11, according to a press
release issued by Dr. Yonzon Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the expedition team led by Dr. Yonzon also found
evidences of the endangered big cat's movements above the 4,000
meter elevation.
</P>
<P>
"Tigers' pugmarks at 4,110 meters suggest that tigers use
expansively high altitude pass to move into adjoining valleys,
said Dr. Yonzon.
</P>
<P>
Yonzon's team has been conducting a wildlife survey in the
ThrumsingLa Park since September 1999.
</P>
<P>
According to Dr. Yonzon, Bhutan's all nine protected areas
contain tiger populations which are connected by wildlife
corridors.
</P>
<P>
Tigers are considered as flagship species, whose existence will
meet habitat requirements of many other species.
</P>
<P>
Only about 6,000 Royal Bengal Tigers are surviving in the parks
and reserves of the South Asian region where they are endemic.
Between 200-250 adult tigers are residing in and around Nepal's
four Terai parks or reserves adjoining to India. 
</P>
</TEXT>
