<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea Export of Semiconductors Increases Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, May 1 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's semiconductor exports
soared 17.4 percent to 5.43 billion U.S. dollars in the first
quarter, compared with the same period last year, the Commerce,
Industry and Energy Ministry said Monday.
</P>
<P>
It will be easy for the nation to meet this year's export
target of 23.5 billion dollars if the current brisk overseas
performance of semiconductor continues, said the ministry.
</P>
<P>
Out of the 5.43 billion dollars, 2.48 billion dollars of
products went to Asia, 1.6 billion dollars to the United States,
560 million dollars to Japan and 760 million dollars to European
countries.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the import of semiconductor reached 4.71 billion
dollars in the first three months, a 23 percent increase over last
year's 3.84 billion dollars, due to the rise of the domestic
demand for computers and mobile phones.
</P>
<P>
Semiconductor export rose as average prices for DRAM chips
dropped by 35 percent to 7.1 dollars a piece from 10.1 dollars,
and the output doubled from 160 million units to 320 million in
the first quarter, said the ministry.
</P>
<P>
The ministry predicted the surplus to be 500 million dollars in
the second quarter of this year with 5.65 billion dollars of
export and 5.15 billion dollars of import based on the stable DRAM
prices and increasing demand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
