<HEADLINE> South Korea Warns of Malaria Risk in 36 Districts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, May 1 (Xinhua) -- South Korea has declared 36 districts
north and west of Seoul as areas for special monitoring against a
malaria epidemic and demanded quarantine measures be taken in
those areas.
</P>
<P>
The 36 districts declared by the South Korean National Health
Institute Sunday included Koyang and Paju, Kyonggi Province. The
infection rate in the 36 districts hovered over 0.1 percent last
year.
</P>
<P>
Health authorities are distributing testing kits, medication
and mosquito repellents to the dangerous zones and advised
officials to quarantine apartment complex underground facilities
as precautionary measures.
</P>
<P>
The institute said Monday that it designated the risk and high-
risk zones after 41 malaria patients were reported at the end of
March.
</P>
<P>
The number of malaria patients, which has been rising in the
past few years, hit 3,621 last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
