<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korean Export by LCs Continues Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, May 1 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's export by letters of
credit (LC) has dropped greatly these years, increasing the risk
for non-payment for exporters, the Bank of Korea said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The export based on LCs accounted for 34.6 percent of the total
in 1999 falling by 15.1 percentage points from 1996's 49.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Export via LCs in the first two months amounted to 7.09 billion
U.S. dollars, accounting for 31.7 percent of the country's total
exports of 22.39 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean central bank attributed the drop to buyers'
reluctance to pay expenses related with establishing LCs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
