<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 6 Killed in Violence in Ambon, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 1 (Xinhua) -- At least six people were killed and
50 others injured when security personnel opened fire to disperse
warring groups in Ambon, capital of Indonesia's Maluku on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The clash also resulted in at least four houses in the
predominantly Christian Mardika district being set alight.
</P>
<P>
The Jakarta Post Monday quoted witnesses as saying that the
conflicting groups used homemade weapons and bombs.
</P>
<P>
The six were reportedly shot by troops in an attempt to scatter
the crowds. The wounded, mostly suffering from gunshot wounds,
were taken to hospital.
</P>
<P>
Tension gripped the town following the shootings, but Pattimura
Military Commander Brig. Gen. Max Tamaela said Sunday night that
the situation in the area was under control.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to quickly restore order, the usual 10 p.m. curfew was
put forward by an hour.
</P>
<P>
"The 9 p.m. curfew will remain until further developments. I
have issued a shoot-on-sight order to anyone who instigates riots.
It is very obvious that certain parties don't want peace to return
in Ambon, I urge people to stay calm," Tamaela was quoted by the
newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
It was the second clash within less than a week to rock the
provincial capital of Ambon, about 2,500 kilometers northeast of
Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
At least three people were killed when mobs threw homemade
bombs at a speedboat off Benteng Gudang Arang in Ambon on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The latest bout of violence took place in the same area where
15 months of communal conflict across the Maluku islands started
in January last year.
</P>
<P>
More than 2,000 people were killed in the prolonged violence,
which also left thousands of homes and buildings destroyed and
hundreds of thousands of people fleeing to other islands and
provinces.
</P>
<P>
Clashes have subsided in recent months but tension remains in
some regions, particularly North Maluku province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000501.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Outbreak of Legionnaires' Disease in Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 1 (Xinhua) -- There was an outbreak of
Legionnaires' disease in Victoria, southeastern Australia,
according to Australian Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
A total of 29 cases were confirmed as legionnaires' and two of
them have died. As many as 56 others were suspected of having
contracted the disease in the recent outbreak.
</P>
<P>
A Victorian Department of Human Services spokesman said the
latest outbreak was attributed to the air-conditioning system at
Melbourne Aquarium.
</P>
<P>
It was the biggest ever in Victoria's history. The previous
largest outbreak led to 17 confirmed cases from an air-
conditioning system in the Melbourne suburb of Thomastown in 1998.
The largest ever outbreak of legionnaires' disease in Australia
was in 1987 in the New South Wales city of Wollongong, where there
were 44 cases and 10 deaths.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister John Howard said on his European tour he would
see a doctor to ensure he had escaped the disease when he visited
the aquarium for a Liberal party function two weeks ago. "I feel
okay - I've got a bit of a cold, but that's got nothing to do with
legionnaires' disease, I don't think," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
West Australian party executive member Neil Patrucco, who
attended the same function, is one of the confirmed cases.
</P>
</TEXT>
