<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Denmark's Ruling Party Endorses Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Denmark's ruling Social
Democratic Party voted in favor of the country's participation in
the European Union's common currency Sunday, reports reaching here
said.
</P>
<P>
At an extraordinary party congress held in Odense, the second
largest city in the country, 486 of the 501 Social Democrats voted
for participation by Denmark in the Economic and Monetary Union (
EMU).
</P>
<P>
However, whether Denmark will join the euro zone will also
hinge upon a referendum to be held on September 28.
</P>
<P>
The common currency has been used in 11 EU countries since
January, 1999 for a better integrated European economy and trade.
Like Britain and Sweden, Denmark, a member of the European Union,
refused in its initial phase, to join the euro zone.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Poul Nyrup Rasmussen told the congress that if
Denmark rejects the euro, then the money speculators on the
world's markets will "throw themselves at us" and pose "the
greatest threat against our welfare system." Thus, he continued, "
Our best insurance against this is adopting the common currency."
</P>
<P>
He said the strong international money markets will shield a "
vulnerable" Denmark against sudden crises, adding that an entry to
the euro zone also means more jobs.
</P>
<P>
A poll published last week showed 46 percent of voters were in
favor of Denmark adopting the single European currency, 44 percent
were against. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
