<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Hopes Objective Report on Kosovo to Be Submitted to U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav Foreign Minister
Zivadin Jovanovic said Sunday that he hoped a visiting U.N.
delegation would submit an objective report on the serious
situation in Kosovo to the U.N. Security Council as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav News Agency Tanjug said Jovanovic made the remarks
during his meeting with Russia's Ambassador to the United Nations,
Sergei Lavrov, a member of the U.N delegation that visited Kosovo
Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In the talks, Lavrov said he felt the situation in Kosovo is
very serious. He described the plight of non-ethnic Albanian
residents there as exceptionally serious. They do not enjoy
fundamental human rights and freedom, Lavrov said.
</P>
<P>
Jovanovic attributed the serious situation to the violation of
U.N. Security Council Resolution 1244 by the U.N. mission in
Kosovo (UNMIK) and the international peacekeeping force (KFOR),
which he said were supporting the separatists of the Kosovar
ethnic Albanians and terrorists in violation of Yugoslavia's
sovereignty and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
He stressed his country would never accept any violation of U.N.
Resolution 1244 issued in June 1999 that ended NATO's air strikes
on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. delegation, consisting of representatives of eight
Security Council members, visited Kosovo Saturday and Sunday to
assess the U.N. mission to rebuild the local government and
infrastructure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
