<HEADLINE> Four GMs Vie for Title in JAPFA Chess Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Four Grand Masters (GMs) will fight
hard to
finish first in the JAPFA Classic International Tournament 2000 in
Bali, Indonesia, on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The clash of the titans will feature lone woman player GM Judit
Polgar of Hungary, GM Anatoly Karpov and GM Alexander Khalifman
both of Russia and GM Gilberto Milos Jr. of Brazil.
</P>
<P>
All four players are getting closer to winning the
championships as they share the top position with 5.5 match points
(MPs) each after eight rounds on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
According to the Jakarta Post Monday, Polgar failed to maintain
her top position after she drew with GM Yasser Seirawan of the
United States in the 23th move on Sunday by Caro Kann defense.
</P>
<P>
Karpov, the FIDE world champion from 1975 to 1985 and from 1993
to 1999, faced a tough challenge from International Master Zaw Win
Lay of Myanmar on Sunday before both players agreed to tie in the
72th move using the Queen Gambit opening.
</P>
<P>
Karpov earned one point to trail Polgar in first place on
Saturday after he defeated GM Jaan Ehlvest of Estonia in the 87th
move by Queen Indian defense in a do-or-die match that lasted for
seven hours.
</P>
<P>
Ehlvest failed to enhance his performance on Sunday and bowed
out to Milos in the 36th move by Sicilia defense.
</P>
<P>
Timman was late to bounce back and gave up to Khalifman after
26 moves on Sunday. They used French defense.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian top players GM Utut Adianto and GM Ruben Gunawan
also drew in the 28th move on Sunday by Queen Gambit declined
opening.
</P>
<P>
Monday will be a day off for the players.
</P>
<P>
Polgar said after the match that she intended to try her very
best to win her final game against Milos on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"I said earlier that I wish to finish in the top three. After
all, it's a very tough tournament. I don't know whether I can beat
Milos, but I'll rest tomorrow (Monday) and we'll see the result on
Tuesday. I will play the black pieces, and it's not going to be
easy," she was quoted by the Jakarta Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
Milos remained noncommital over his chances of winning over
Polgar, given the results of their five previous meets where
Polgar won three out of five and Milos won only once. They drew
once.
</P>
<P>
"I'm not sure (that I can beat her). I have the chance to win
and so does Judit. But I'm very happy with my performance in this
tournament," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also hoped he could finish in the top three in the 16th
category event held at the Grand Bali Beach hotel in Denpasar,
capital of Bali.
</P>
<P>
Following is the standings after eight rounds:
</P>
<P>
Polgar, 5.5 points
</P>
<P>
Karpov, 5.5
</P>
<P>
Khalifman, 5.5
</P>
<P>
Milos 5.5
</P>
<P>
Seirawan, 4.5
</P>
<P>
Utut, 3.5
</P>
<P>
Timman, 3
</P>
<P>
Ehlvest 3
</P>
<P>
Gunawan, 2.5
</P>
<P>
