<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Resolution of Hostage Crisis Proves Tough By Chen Hegao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government now is
beset by two hostage crises, one involving foreigners, and the
other all Filipinos. But the resolution of the hostage crises,
either by force or by talks, has proved very difficult.
</P>
<P>
Until now, no one could predict when the two groups of hostages
could be rescued or freed, observers said.
</P>
<P>
The first hostage crisis started on March 20, when the Muslim
extremist group Abu Sayyaf took away more than 50 people from two
schools in Basilan as a human shield after attacking a government
army post. Later the rebels held 29 of them as hostages and freed
the rest. Most of the hostages are school children and their
teachers.
</P>
<P>
The second crisis began on April 23. A group of Abu Sayyaf
members abducted 21 tourists and staff members from a diving
resort in Sipadan, Malaysia and moved to Jolo Island in the
southern Philippine Province of Sulu.
</P>
<P>
The hostages include two French, three Germans, two South
Africans, two Finns, one Lebanese, two Filipinos and several
Malaysian resort workers and wildlife experts.
</P>
<P>
Although the Philippine government has made all-out efforts to
rescue the two groups of hostages, the resolution of the crises
seems not easy.
</P>
<P>
On April 19, the Abu Sayyaf group claimed to have beheaded two
male hostages as Manila and Washington rejected its demand for the
release of two Abu Sayyaf members and three terrorists jailed in
the United States, including Ramzi Yousef, the mastermind of the
1993 bombing of the World Trade Center in New York.
</P>
<P>
The claim prompted the Philippine government to use force to
rescue the hostages. During the past week, government troops used
military helicopters and planes to attack the Abu Sayyaf camps.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday, the government army overran the mountain
stronghold of the Abu Sayyaf group and killed dozens of rebels,
but found no trace of hostages.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, the troops prepared to put tear gas into the tunnels
where the rebels and hostages may stay. But the troops are unsure
if the rebels and hostages are inside the tunnels.
</P>
<P>
According to a claim by Abu Sayyaf members over the radio, the
rebels and 27 hostages have already fled together into the jungles.
</P>
<P>
An army general said Monday morning that their "main concern
now is to get the hostages alive."
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that since the rebels have secret tunnels in the
area and can escape when they are attacked, it is very difficult
for government troops to rescue the hostages in the mountain area,
where the rebels have planted many landmines.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the Abu Sayyaf is the most violent rebel group in the
Philippines. They could kill hostages if they fail to escape in
the fighting, they said.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf, which means "Father of the Executioner" in
Arabic, is fighting for an Islamic state in the Southern
Philippines, though it has no more than 500 members.
</P>
<P>
As for the second hostage crisis, negotiations between the
government and the rebels have not started yet despite their
initial contacts.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, the Abu Sayyaf group threatened to behead some of
the 21 hostages they abducted in Malaysia, because they did not
want to talk with a government negotiator -- Nur Misuari, governor
of the Autonomous Region of Muslim Mindanao and leader of the
former anti-government Moro National Liberation Front.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Abu Sayyaf said that his group wanted to
talk with the ambassadors of the countries to which their captives
belong.
</P>
<P>
"Misuari is trying to divide and rule us. Because of this we
decided tonight (Friday) to rejected Misuari as the government
negotiator," the spokesman said. "Instead we demand the
ambassadors of the respective countries of these captives to
negotiate with us, and if they do not want, we will behead some of
the foreigners to teach them a lesson."
</P>
<P>
"We will execute the foreign captives and we will embarrass the
Philippine government," he added.
</P>
<P>
However, the Philippine government said it will not replace the
negotiator and will resolve the hostage crisis in Sulu by peaceful
means.
</P>
<P>
Acting Armed Forces chief of staff Jose Calimlim told reporters
that he received a lot of inquiries from foreign ambassadors based
in Manila asking about the condition of the hostages.
</P>
<P>
Calimlim said he assured them that the government will exert
all efforts for the safe release of the hostages as soon as
possible, but he refused to give a timetable.
</P>
<P>
"It is difficult to set a time frame when the hostages would be
freed," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Calimlim, the hostages are being guarded by about
40 to 50 gunmen in Talipao in the southern Philippine island
province of Sulu.
</P>
<P>
Calimlim note that government soldiers have sealed off the area
to prevent the kidnappers from escaping. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000501.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afghan Opposition Commander Defects to Taliban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 1 (Xinhua) -- An eminent opposition commander in
Afghanistan has recently defected to the ruling Taliban militia
along with some 3,000 supporters, news reports reaching here said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Commander Abdullah Jan, who controlled the Daulat Shahi
district in the eastern Afghan province of Laghaman, told a news
conference Sunday that he decided not to fight against Taliban
troops after realizing the "futility" of lasting civil war in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Jan, an ally of chief opposition commander Ahmad Shah Masood,
addressed the press conference in Kabul along with the Taliban's
Foreign Minister Wakil Ahmad Mutawakel and Defense Minister
Mawlawi Obaidllah.
</P>
<P>
Daulat Shahi is a strategically crucial district, located at
the access to Masood's stronghold of Panjsher valley northeast of
Kabul.
</P>
<P>
Jan, who joined the ruling militia a week ago, said some 3,000
armed troops under his command also joined the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
However, he said he would not fight against Masood and voiced
the hope there would be no need for any fighting in Afghanistan,
which has been ravaged by civil war for two decades.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, who have more than 80 percent of the Afghan
territory under their control, are fighting opposition troops
loyal to Masood in the northern part of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
