<DOCNO> XIE20000501.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Educates Citizens Against Household Fires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Beijing has launched a campaign to
educate local residents against possible household fires at its
largest Fangzhuang Residential Zone.
</P>
<P>
This marks the beginning of a nationwide campaign called "
Keeping Households Away From Fires".
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that in 1999 alone, there were 22,000 fires
broke out at urban residential buildings, killing 673 and injured
945 people, and leaving damage bill costing 110 million yuan (13.
25 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
China's fire-fighting departments said that people lack a basic
awareness of fire-prevention and have little or no idea about how
to extinguish fires or escape from them.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Public Security, the State Administration of
Radio, Film and Television, All-China Women's Federation and the
People's Insurance Company of China have combined their efforts to
a nationwide campaign to publicize fire prevention all over the
country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000501.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourism Index of Major Chinese Regions: Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The following is the tourism
development in Beijing, the Chinese capital, in the first quarter
of the year:
</P>
<P>
Some 459,000 tourists from overseas visited Beijing in the
quarter, representing an increase of 14.6 percent over last year's
same period. Among the total number of tourists, alien visitors
reached 379,000, up 20.1 percent, 5.5 percentage points above the
average growth rate.
</P>
<P>
More than 192,000 Asian tourists visited the city, making up
half of the total, and the number of tourists from Europe and
America climbed 7.3 percent and 1.4 percent, respectively.
</P>
</TEXT>
