<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Retailers Enjoy Business Boom in Dalian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The total volume of retail sales by
the overseas-invested retail enterprises (OIRE) in Dalian, a port
city of Liaoning Province in Northeast China, has boomed in the
first quarter.
</P>
<P>
The retailers have realized a total volume of 670 million yuan
(80.7 U.S. dollars), up 45.9 percent over last year, while the
average increase rate of the industry in the city is only 11.9
percent, according to the Dalian City Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
The business volume represents 6.4 percent of local retailing
market, compared with 1.5 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
As retail industry becomes the hot point for the overseas
investment, eight world-renowned retail enterprises including
Carefour, have set up branches in the city.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000501.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Upgrade of Qinghai-Tibet Railway To Start In May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Upgrading of the 825.9 km Xining-
Golmud section of the Qinghai-Tibet Railway line will begin this
month.
</P>
<P>
The 740-million-yuan (89 million U.S. dollars) project should
be finished by October of 2001, a spokesman for the work said
today.
</P>
<P>
Listed as one of China's major State-funded projects, the new
rail section is aimed to increase the line's handling capacity by
30 percent to meet the growing demand.
</P>
<P>
At present, the line can move six million tons of goods and 3.
13 million passengers each year. It is estimated that about 9.86
million tons of locally produced oil, ore and raw salt is
transported out of the Qinghai Province annually.
</P>
<P>
The Qinghai-Tibet railway line has handled 180 million tons of
goods and 80 million passengers since it opened in 1984.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
