<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sanctions, War of Massive Slaughter: Iraqi Speaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Speaker of the Iraqi National Assembly
Saadoun Hamadi on Monday blamed the decade-old sanctions by the
United Nations on his country as a war of massive slaughter which
has claimed lives of over 1 million people.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark in his speech at the 103rd conference of the
Inter-Parliamentary Union (IPU), a six-day biannual event
inaugurated in Amman on Sunday to discuss world peace and stability
as well as dialogue between different cultures and civilizations.
</P>
<P>
Hamadi said the U.N. sanctions, imposed after Iraqi troops
invaded neighboring Kuwait in 1990, had been more barbarous than
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
By the end of April, he said, the sanctions had claimed lives of
1.3 million Iraqi citizens, most of whom are children.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the sanctions, he said, the mortality rates
increased by seven and four times for Iraqi children below and
above the age of five respectively, and many children either
suffered from malnutrition or had to drop out of school due to
deteriorating living standards and rising unemployment rates in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Basic infrastructure in important economic sectors of Iraq were
also severely damaged by the crippling sanctions, hence an
obstacles to the development of his country, he added.
</P>
<P>
Hamadi claimed that Iraq has implemented U.N. resolutions on
Iraq and had fully cooperated with a U.N. special committee on
weapons inspections in his country, but the U.N. and had failed to
carry out its commitments to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions can be lifted only after U.N. weapons experts
certify that Iraq has dismantled all its weapons of mass
destruction. The U.N. Security Council has adopted a new resolution
on restarting weapons inspection in exchange for phased removal of
the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad has rejected the resolution, accusing it of
backpedalling on a promised full lifting of sanctions upon Iraqi
compliance.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi speaker also blamed the U.N. inaction to the no-fly
zones imposed in the north and south of Iraq by U.S. and British
forces since 1991, under the excuse of preventing Iraqi government
prosecution of Kurds and Shiite Muslims.
</P>
<P>
The daily patrols by U.S. and British fighter planes in the air
exclusion zones, which Baghdad never recognizes for lack of U.N.
authorization, are daily aggression against Iraq, he added.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to world countries for endorsing the establishment
of a new international order based on balance, justice, respect for
human rights and dialogue.
</P>
<P>
The IPU, founded in 1889 and now has 144 members, is the largest
international parliamentary organization.
</P>
<P>
Its biannual conference serves as an important venue for
parliamentarians of countries under different political systems to
discuss global issues of common concern. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
