<DOCNO> XIE20000501.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Dismisses U.S. Charges of Supporting Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Iran on Monday dismissed the U.S.
charges that it supports terrorism, saying the accusations were a
way of diverting public attention from the behavior of Israel.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman Hamid Reza Asefi said that by
accusing Iran of terrorism, the United States is in fact trying to
divert international attention from Israel, which Iran terms as the
main supporter of terrorism in the Middle East region.
</P>
<P>
Quoted by the Islamic Republic News Agency, Asefi said that
Iran "has always been a victim of terrorism," adding that the U.S.
accusations showed its "dishonesty toward this odious phenomenon."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. State Department released a report Friday listing Iran
as the main supporter of terrorism in the region.
</P>
<P>
Although there were signs of political change in Iran in 1999,
the actions of certain state institutions in support of terrorist
groups made Iran the most active state sponsor of terrorism, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Iran supports the Shiite Muslim Hezbollah, or Party of God,
which is leading a guerrilla war to end Israel's 22-year-old
occupation of south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Tehran and Washington were severed in 1980
after Iranian students seized the U.S. embassy in Tehran and held
52 Americans hostage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
