<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Center of Anti-American Terrorism Shifts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. State Department issued
an annual report on anti-American terrorism, saying the focus of
terrorism has shifted from the Middle East to South Asia.
</P>
<P>
"1999 saw a shift from the Middle East to South Asia as a focus
of terrorism against the United States," a State Department
official said upon the release of the 107-page annual report,
entitled "Patterns of Global Terrorism - 1999," which was sent to
Congress last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The State Department's report also said that the anti-American
terrorism trends have shifted from well organized, localized
groups supported by state sponsors to "loosely organized
international networks of terrorists."
</P>
<P>
The report said the eastward shift of anti-American terrorist
centers to South Asia occurred after most Middle East governments
strengthened their counter-terrorist response.
</P>
<P>
"In South Asia, the major terrorist threat comes from
Afghanistan, which continues to be the primary safe haven for
terrorists," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The United States picked up Afghanistan as the "major terrorist
threat" because the State Department said it "continues to harbor
Osama bin Laden and a host of other terrorists loosely linked to
bin Laden, who directly threaten the United States and others in
the international community."
</P>
<P>
In Kabul, the Taliban government said in a statement that bin
Laden is a guest and Afghan tradition forbids handing him over to
an enemy. The statement also condemned terrorism as against Islam.
</P>
<P>
The State Department report also said Pakistan sends mixed
messages on terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"Despite significant and material cooperation in some areas --
particularly arrests and extraditions -- the Pakistani government
also has tolerated terrorists living and moving freely within its
territory," the report said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan denied the charges, saying the so-called terrorist
link was unfounded.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan is irrevocably opposed to terrorism in all its forms.
Pakistan has always cooperated with the international community,
including the United States, to combat terrorism," a Pakistani
Foreign Ministry spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He also dismissed U.S. demands that the Islamabad government
use its key influence with the Taliban government in Afghanistan
to get bin Laden extradited, saying Washington must deal directly
with the Taliban over the matter.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan ... cannot be expected to interfere in the internal
affairs of Afghanistan," he read a Pakistani statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
