<HEADLINE> Tanzanian President Defends Economic Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President Benjamin
Mkapa defended on Monday the ongoing economic reforms in the
country, saying they are inevitable to absorb shocks from the
developed world.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the May Day rally in the central town of Dodoma, the
 president said poor countries are fighting with big nations in an
 environment which has no boundaries of capital, trade, production
and markets, a situation which has enabled the latter to control
the world economy.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania and other poor countries must brace up and learn the
game's tricks and procedures so that they could as well play it
and "win goals," the president said in his candid 38-page speech.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa emphasized that his government would continue the
economic reforms so that the economy could grow by at least six
percent this year.
</P>
<P>
"We should stop hating foreign companies taking over our firms
and instead work with them to increase production and safeguard
employment," the president said.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania has made substantial progress in implementing economic
reforms. During the last four years, inflation came down to less
than 7 percent from over 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
The structural reform agenda includes the restructuring and
privatization of utilities and other parastatal monopolies and the
implementation of regulatory frameworks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
