<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Rise Broadly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks rose Monday
despite a recommendation for breaking up Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
At the close of session, the Dow Jones industrial average rose
77.87 at 10,811.78.The index fell 154.19 points last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also higher. The technology heavy
Nasdaq composite index rose 97.42 at 3,958.08 in the third
consecutive session and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index rose 15.82
at 1,468.25.
</P>
<P>
Stocks rallied as investors moved into the market for bargain-
hunting, defying the U.S. Justice Department's recommendation made
last Friday for splitting Microsoft into two companies. Microsoft
rose in the first session after the recommendation.
</P>
<P>
The company has suffered heavy losses since U.S. District Judge
Thomas Penfield Jackson ruled on April 4 that Microsoft had
repeatedly violated the antitrust law.Investors believed today a
possible breakup of Microsoft had already taken its toll on the
company's stocks.
</P>
<P>
Investors were also encouraged by a report from the U.S.
National Association of Purchasing Management. The report said
America's industrial sector grew for the 15th consecutive month in
April but prices for raw materials did not rise as fast as in the
earlier months, easing fears in inflation.
</P>
<P>
Other tech companies including dot.coms were also higher. Among
them were Red Hat, VA Linux and About.com.
</P>
<P>
General Electric led the Dow's advance.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index 6.41 at 650.57 and the American Stock Exchange
index rose 13.73 at 936.18. The Russell 2000 index of smaller
companies rose 12.68 at 518.93.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by nearly a 2-to-1
margin on the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,959 up, 1,055 down
and 432 unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume declined to 943.85 million shares from 970.34
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
