<HEADLINE> Hiroshima, Nagasaki Call for Nuclear Weapons-Free World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 1(Xinhua) -- The Mayors of Hiroshima and
Nagasaki of Japan on Monday urged the United Nations to help bring
about a nuclear weapons-free world.
</P>
<P>
Itcho Ito, Mayor of Nagasaki, delivered the appeal on behalf of
the two cities to the U.N. Deputy Secretary-General for
Disarmament Affairs, Jayantha Dhanapala, and Addallah Baali,
Chairman of the current U.N. conference on nuclear
nonproliferation.
</P>
<P>
Ito and Hiroshi Morimoto, the deputy Hiroshima mayor, are here
in New York to attend the 2000 Review Conference of the Parties to
the Treaty on the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons (NPT) which
is held at the Headquarters of the United Nations from April 24 to
May 19.
</P>
<P>
The two mayors said in their appeal that the nuclear non-
proliferation regime was facing a collapse following the nuclear
tests in 1998 by South Asia.
</P>
<P>
They expressed the hope that the current 2000 Review Conference
on NPT would produce concrete results on nuclear arms reduction.
</P>
<P>
Ito is expected to address the conference Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Hiroshima and Nagasaki are the world's only nuclear-bombed
cities.
</P>
<P>
Opened for signature in 1968, the Treaty entered into force in
1970. By January 2000, a total of 187 parties have joined the
Treaty, including the five nuclear weapons states.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
