<HEADLINE> U.S. Companies Asked to Give Donation to War Reparation Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
U.S. Deputy Treasury Secretary Stuart Eizenstat said the
companies should consider paying into the fund regardless of
whether they had German subsidiaries in Nazi time. .
</P>
<P>
Nazis nationalized some 50 U.S. companies including some major
ones still operating in Europe, Eizenstat said, adding that one of
the aims to set up the fund is to avert the threat of class-action
lawsuits against these companies.
</P>
<P>
The fund will channel corporate donations to victims of natural
disasters, the former slave and forced laborers and other
humanitarian purposes.
</P>
<P>
Craig Johnstone, the chamber's senior vice president for
international affairs, said the project is the result of requests
from a number of member companies.
</P>
<P>
Several large American corporations, including Ford and General
Motors, have acknowledged that their German subsidiaries benefited
from slave labor after operations were taken over by the German
government during World War II.
</P>
<P>
Some of the U.S. companies have asked to use the Chamber fund
to supplement the compensation payments from a 5.2 billion U.S.
dollars German fund, according to Eizenstat.
</P>
<P>
The German government and companies last year agreed to pay 10
billion German marks to establish a fund to compensate the Nazi
forced laborers and slaves.
</P>
<P>
Eizenstat said that he hopes the U.S. fund will "facilitate the
settlement of existing suits and avoid the filing of new and
additional suits which would be very time-consuming, very
debilitating." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
