<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Rejects U.S. Accusation on Handling of Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ATHENS, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Greece Monday rejected the U.S.
accusation of its position in dealing with terrorism.
</P>
<P>
In an annual report published by the U.S. State Department
Monday, Washington said that Greek terrorists last year
perpetrated 20 acts of violence against concerns of the U.S.
government and U.S. private companies in Greece and dramatically
increased their attacks against Greek targets, as well as foreign
targets.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. also complained that the absence of a strong public
leading government position and of initiatives to improve the
capabilities and morale of the police, contributed to the lack of
successes against terrorists.
</P>
<P>
Greece Monday described the U.S. accusation of its position
against terrorism as unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
"The Greek government believes that direct or indirect
accusations on Greece's policy on the issue of terrorism can not
be accepted, " Greek government spokesman Dimitris Reppas said at
a press briefing.
</P>
<P>
He added that Greece remained steadfastly bent on the target
of confronting the phenomenon of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman stressed that Athens was standing in the front-
line in combating terrorism and was participating actively in all
international efforts, on an equal basis, with the criterion of
domestic law and order and respect for democratic institutions and
rights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
